		'resource_type' : NULL,
		'title' : 'CMS providers coders guidance on assigning 7th character to indicate trimester of pregnancy',
		'published' : '2012-03-15 15:44:47',
		'status' : 0,
		'summary' : '',
		'body' : '<a href=\"http://blogs.hcpro.com/icd-10/wp-content/uploads/2012/03/physdoc01_2834090.jpg\"><img class=\"alignright size-thumbnail wp-image-2580\" title=\"physdoc01_2834090\" src=\"http://blogs.hcpro.com/icd-10/wp-content/uploads/2012/03/physdoc01_2834090-150x150.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"150\" height=\"150\" /></a>Will coders be allowed to calculate and assign the final ICD-10-CM character for the trimester of pregnancy based on the estimated date of conception?\r\n\r\nRecently a coder asked me regarding the documentation and assignment of the seventh character, which identifies the trimester of pregnancy, would a coder be able to take the estimated date of conception (EDC) and calculate the trimester in order to assign the final character? I wasn’t sure whether CMS had addressed this yet, so I went to my Draft <em>ICD-10-CM Manual</em>, Chapter 15: Pregnancy, Childbirth, and the Puerperium and was pleasantly surprised to discover that the Draft <em>ICD-10-CM Official Guidelines for Coding and Reporting</em> had indeed addressed this topic. It appears the answer to the question is no, they won’t be able to calculate the trimester based on the EDC.\r\n\r\nThe Draft <em>ICD-10-CM Official Coding Guidelines for Coding and Reporting</em> state:\r\n<p style=\"padding-left: 30px;\"><em>Assignment of the final character for trimester should be based on the provider’s documentation of the trimester (or number of weeks) for the current admission/encounter. This applies to the assignment of trimester for pre-existing conditions as well as those that develop during or are due to the pregnancy. The provider’s documentation of the number of weeks may be used to assign the appropriate code identifying the trimester.</em></p>\r\nUnfortunately, the guidelines do not address the ability of the coder to calculate the trimester based on the EDC.\r\n\r\nThis does not surprise me as this seems to follow current ICD-9-CM  guidelines on documentation when it comes to coders and calculations. For example, coders are not allowed to calculate the body mass index. The provider or the dietician/nursing notes must supply that documentation.\r\n\r\nAlthough some may not agree with the guidelines for the various documentation nightmares we see, I for one appreciate the definition between coder vs. physician. After all, it is the physician’s responsibility to ensure that his or her documentation is legible, complete, clear, consistent, and precise, as well as accurate and reliable. The documentation should include the history, present illness, course of treatment, outcome of all tests, procedures, and treatments, and  be specific enough in terms of anatomical sites and etiologies of symptoms to support the assigned codes.\r\n\r\nAnd when it comes to the various antepartum complications, some conditions occur only in certain trimesters, and therefore it is important that the physician identify the specificity for proper code assignment.',
		'meta_keywords' : '',
		'volume' : NULL,
		'issue' : NULL,
		'article_position' : NULL
