		'title' : 'Note ICD-10-CM guideline changes for neoplasms',
		'published' : '2012-01-10 14:00:07',
		'status' : 1,
		'summary' : '',
		'body' : 'The 2012 ICD-10-CM updates include significant narrative changes for primary malignant neoplasms overlapping site boundaries and malignant neoplasm of ectopic tissue, as well as smaller narrative changes to coding and sequencing of complications.\r\n\r\nICD-10-CM instructs coders to classify a primary malignant neoplasm that overlaps two or more contiguous (next to each other) sites to the subcategory/code .8 (\'overlapping lesion\'), unless the combination is specifically indexed elsewhere. For multiple neoplasms of the same site that are not contiguous, such as tumors in different quadrants of the same breast, coders  should assign a code for each site.\r\n\r\nFor malignant neoplasm of ectopic tissue, code the malignant neoplasm to the site mentioned. For example, code an ectopic pancreatic malignant neoplasm to pancreas, unspecified (C25.9).\r\n\r\nWhen a patient is admitted or sees a provider for management of an anemia associated with the malignancy, and receives treatment only for anemia, report the code for the malignancy as the principal or first-listed diagnosis followed by the appropriate code for the anemia.\r\n\r\nWhen a patient is admitted or sees a provider for management of an anemia associated with an adverse effect of the administration of chemotherapy or immunotherapy and receives treatment only for the anemia, sequenced the anemia code first followed by the appropriate codes for the neoplasm and the adverse effect.',
		'meta_keywords' : '',
		'volume' : NULL,
		'issue' : NULL,
		'article_position' : NULL
