		'resource_type' : NULL,
		'title' : 'Blisters, broken toes, and bursitis ',
		'published' : '2012-04-04 12:04:43',
		'status' : 1,
		'summary' : '',
		'body' : '<img class=\"alignright\" title=\"Feet\" src=\"http://openclipart.org/people/inky2010/1281031798.svg\" alt=\"\" width=\"223\" height=\"175\" />My feet are killing me. I wonder what the problem is. Let’s see what it could be and how we would code it in ICD-10-CM.\r\n\r\nI got a new pair of shoes, so maybe the problem is a blister. That should be easy to code, right? When we look up blister in the ICD-9-CM alphabetic index, it tells us to look up injury, superficial, by site. Couldn’t they just list it under blister?\r\n\r\nWhen we head to foot, we find only two codes for blisters of the feet and toes–blister without mention of infection (917.2) and blister, infected (917.3).\r\n\r\nWhen we look in the ICD-10-CM alphabetic index, we actually find a whole list of possibilities under the term \'blister\'. Okay, so that’s easier. When we find foot, we get code S90.82-. Don’t forget that the dash means we need more characters. A note in the index also tells us not to use this code for blisters of the toes. They have their own set of codes.\r\n\r\nSo off we go to the S90.82- series where we find only three choices:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>S90.821, blister (nonthermal), right foot</li>\r\n	<li>S90.822, blister (nonthermal), left foot</li>\r\n	<li>S90.829, blister (nonthermal), unspecified foot</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nHowever, unlike ICD-9-CM, ICD-10-CM includes separate codes for a blister on the toe:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>S90.421, blister (nonthermal), right great toe</li>\r\n	<li>S90.422, blister (nonthermal), left great toe</li>\r\n	<li>S90.423, blister (nonthermal), unspecified great toe</li>\r\n	<li>S90.424, blister (nonthermal), right lesser toe(s)</li>\r\n	<li>S90.425, blister (nonthermal), left lesser toe(s)</li>\r\n	<li>S90.426, blister (nonthermal), unspecified lesser toe(s)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nWe need a seventh character for all of the blister codes to indicate the encounter, so that will expand our possible code choices. Notice that the ICD-10-CM codes include laterality, but no notation of infection. ICD-10-CM also specifies that the blisters are nonthermal, meaning the blister was not caused by heat.\r\n\r\nIf it’s not a blister, what else could it be?  Maybe I fractured a toe. Every time I drop something, it seems to land on my toes. In ICD-9-CM, we can choose between a closed toe fracture (826.0) and an open toe fracture (826.1). Since nothing is sticking out and the skin isn’t broken, I’m going with closed toe fracture.\r\n\r\nWhen we get to ICD-10-CM, the coding gets a lot more complicated. We need to know which toe was fractured. Was it the great toe or a lesser toe? The great toe has its own codes, while the lesser toes are all lumped together. That seems kind of unfair, doesn’t it?\r\n\r\nOnce we know which toe, we need to know which side, whether the fracture is displaced or nondisplaced, and whether the break is on the distal or proximal phalanx. Here’s hoping that physician documents thoroughly.\r\n\r\nFor example, if the physician documents an initial visit for a displaced fracture of the proximal phalanx of the left great toe, we would code S92.412A. As with all fracture codes, we need that seventh character to indicate the episode of care.\r\n\r\nMaybe the problem isn’t with my foot, but with my ankle. It could be bursitis. ICD-9-CM includes only one option—726.79 (enthesopthy of ankle and tarsus, other).\r\n\r\nICD-10-CM, not surprisingly, offers more choices for bursitis of the ankle, including:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>M06.271, rheumatoid bursitis, right ankle and foot</li>\r\n	<li>M06.272, rheumatoid bursitis, left ankle and foot</li>\r\n	<li>M06.279, rheumatoid bursitis, unspecified ankle and foot</li>\r\n	<li>M10.071, idiopathic gout (also known as gouty bursitis), right ankle and foot</li>\r\n	<li>M10.072, idiopathic gout, left ankle and foot</li>\r\n	<li>M10.079, idiopathic gout, unspecified ankle and foot</li>\r\n	<li>M70.871, other soft tissue disorders related to use, overuse and pressure, right ankle and foot</li>\r\n	<li>M70.872, other soft tissue disorders related to use, overuse and pressure, left ankle and foot</li>\r\n	<li>M70.879, other soft tissue disorders related to use, overuse and pressure, unspecified ankle and foot</li>\r\n	<li>M71.171, other infective bursitis, right ankle and foot</li>\r\n	<li>M71.172, other infective bursitis, left ankle and foot</li>\r\n	<li>M71.179, other infective bursitis, unspecified ankle and foot</li>\r\n	<li>M71.571, other bursitis, not elsewhere classified, right ankle and foot</li>\r\n	<li>M71.572, other bursitis, not elsewhere classified, left ankle and foot</li>\r\n	<li>M71.579, other bursitis, not elsewhere classified, unspecified ankle and foot</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nWow, that’s a lot of choices. I think I’ll let podiatrist figure it out.',
		'meta_keywords' : '',
