		'summary' : '',
		'body' : 'When a physician moves a body part to a new place without disrupting its vascular and nervous supply, coders will code to root operation Transfer in ICD-10-PCS. The root operation is indicated by the third character of the code. Note that the transferred body part remains connected to its vascular and nervous supply throughout a Transfer procedure.\r\n\r\nThe body system value (second character) describes the deepest tissue layer in the flap. The qualifier can be used to describe the other tissue layers, if any, that are transferred. When the physician uses more than one tissue layer in the transfer procedure, such as in a musculocutaneous flap transfer, coders should report the appropriate qualifiers.\r\n\r\nExamples of Transfer procedures include:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>0LX70ZZ, right hand open palmaris longus tendon transfer.</li>\r\n	<li>01X64Z5, endoscopic radial to median nerve transfer.</li>\r\n	<li>0JXM0ZC, fasciocutaneous flap closure of left thigh, open.  The qualifier identifies the body layers in addition to fascia included in the procedure.</li>\r\n	<li>0JX43ZZ, percutaneous fascia transfer to fill defect, anterior neck.</li>\r\n	<li>0LXP4ZZ, endoscopic left leg flexor hallucis longus tendon transfer.</li>\r\n	<li>0HX6XZZ, skin transfer flap closure of complex open wound, left lower back.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n&nbsp;',
