		'title' : 'Occupational hazards to your lung health',
		'published' : '2012-07-18 15:49:58',
		'status' : 1,
		'summary' : '',
		'body' : 'I grew up in Western Pennsylvania coal country, where coal mines at one time were prevalent and back in the day, you could smell the hydrogen sulphide (at least according to my mother).\r\n\r\nA lot of the people who worked in the mines had (or thought they had) black lung as a result of exposure to coal dust. Out of curiosity, I looked up black lung in ICD-10-CM and found out coal mining is not the only job that can be hazardous to your lung health.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://blogs.hcpro.com/icd-10/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/shutterstock_73841773.jpg\"><img class=\"alignright size-medium wp-image-2879\" title=\"ICD-10 lung coding\" src=\"http://blogs.hcpro.com/icd-10/wp-content/uploads/2012/07/shutterstock_73841773-213x300.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"213\" height=\"300\" /></a>You’ll find the codes for lung diseases due to external agents in the J60-J70 codes in ICD-10-CM. Among them is J60, coalworker\'s pneumoconiosis, also known as black lung. J60 also includes anthracosilicosism, anthracosis, and coalworker\'s lung. It excludes coalworker pneumoconiosis with tuberculosis, any type. That is an Exludes1 note, which means the condition is not coded here. An Excludes1 note indicates that the code excluded should never be reported with the code above the Excludes1 note.\r\n\r\nIf you scan down the list of codes, you’ll also find these occupational health hazards, among others:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>J62.0, pneumoconiosis due to talc dust</li>\r\n	<li>J62.8, pneumoconiosis due to other dust containing silica</li>\r\n	<li>J66, airway disease due to specific organic dust</li>\r\n	<li>J66.1, flax-dressers\' disease</li>\r\n	<li>J67.0, farmer\'s lung (also known as harvester\'s lung, haymaker\'s lung, and moldy hay disease)</li>\r\n	<li>J67.2, bird fancier\'s lung</li>\r\n	<li>J67.4, maltworker\'s lung</li>\r\n	<li>J67.5, mushroom-worker\'s lung</li>\r\n	<li>J67.6, maple-bark-stripper\'s lung</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nA patient may also suffer from:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Cheese-washer\'s lung</li>\r\n	<li>Coffee-worker\'s lung</li>\r\n	<li>Fish-meal worker\'s lung</li>\r\n	<li>Furrier\'s lung</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nThose all fall under J67.8 (hypersensitivity pneumonitis due to other organic dusts)\r\n\r\nThat’s certainly not an exhaustive list and most of the codes are pretty straightforward. Nothing really tricky about them, as long as the physician documents the disease.\r\n\r\nCoders who work in pulmonology will likely see these cases more commonly than any other specialty, but it’s always good to know what’s in the code book. And to be really, really glad you don’t work in any of these jobs.',
