		'status' : 1,
		'summary' : '',
		'body' : 'The American Osteopathic Association (AOA) House of Delegates has joined the American Medical Association’s (AMA) crusade to crush ICD-10 implementation.\r\n\r\nBack in November 2011, the AMA’s House of Delegates voted to “work vigorously to stop implementation of ICD-10” during the closing session of its semi-annual policy-making meeting.\r\n\r\nThe AOA isn’t going quite that far, but the House of Delegates did vote to oppose full implementation of ICD-10 during its 2012 annual meeting in Chicago. And the AOA may not be as dedicated to stopping ICD-10 as the AMA: only 51% of delegates voted in favor of the AOA voicing its disapproval.\r\n\r\nIn response to the AMA’s declaration, the Department of Health and Human Services (HHS) decided to investigate delaying ICD-10 implementation and eventually proposed a one-year delay. We still have no final word on whether HHS is actually changing the date and if so, what the new compliance date will be.',
