		'summary' : '',
		'body' : 'We’ve all heard of deranged killers, but have you ever heard of a deranged knee? Better yet, can you code for it?\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://blogs.hcpro.com/icd-10/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/Knee-joint.jpg\"><img class=\"alignright size-medium wp-image-2966\" title=\"ICD-10 knee derangement\" src=\"http://blogs.hcpro.com/icd-10/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/Knee-joint-300x246.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"246\" /></a>Coding for a derangement isn’t new. We have derangement codes in ICD-9-CM. For example, code series 717 contains codes for various internal derangements of the knee, including:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>717.0, old bucket handle tear of medial meniscus</li>\r\n	<li>717.1, derangement of anterior horn of medial meniscus</li>\r\n	<li>717.2, derangement of posterior horn of medial meniscus</li>\r\n	<li>717.3, other and unspecified derangement of medial meniscus</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nIn most cases, the codes are fairly general. In fact, you don’t need any additional specification until you hit\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>717.4, derangement of lateral meniscus</li>\r\n	<li>717.8, other internal derangement of knee</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nThese two categories require a fifth digit that supplies additional detail.\r\n\r\nIn ICD-10-CM, internal derangements of the knee fall under M23.- and that category includes a lot more codes.\r\n\r\nYou’ll also find a Excludes1 note (meaning not coded here) for the following conditions:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Ankylosis (M24.66)</li>\r\n	<li>Current injury - see injury of knee and lower leg (S80-S89)</li>\r\n	<li>Deformity of knee (M21.-)</li>\r\n	<li>Osteochondritis dissecans (M93.2)</li>\r\n	<li>Recurrent dislocation or subluxation of joints (M24.4)</li>\r\n	<li>Recurrent dislocation or subluxation of patella (M22.0-M22.1)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nAlmost all of the codes under category M23.- require a six-digit code, but none require a seventh character.\r\n\r\nWhen we look at the possibilities for types of knee derangement, we find the following general subcategories:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>M23.0, cystic meniscus</li>\r\n	<li>M23.2, derangement of meniscus due to old tear or injury</li>\r\n	<li>M23.3, other meniscus derangements</li>\r\n	<li>M23.4, loose body in knee</li>\r\n	<li>M23.5, chronic instability of knee</li>\r\n	<li>M23.6, other spontaneous disruption of ligament(s) of knee</li>\r\n	<li>M23.8, other internal derangements of knee</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nAll of the codes include a character to indicate laterality:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>0 or 9 for unspecified, depending on the code series</li>\r\n	<li>1 for right</li>\r\n	<li>2 for left</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nFor codes under M23.4 and M23.5, that information occupies the fifth character position. For the remaining codes, that information is noted in the sixth character. So for example, if a patient suffers a spontaneous disruption of medial collateral ligament, you would choose one of these codes:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>M23.631, other spontaneous disruption of medial collateral ligament of right knee</li>\r\n	<li>M23.632, other spontaneous disruption of medial collateral ligament of left knee</li>\r\n	<li>M23.639, other spontaneous disruption of medial collateral ligament of unspecified knee</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nBe sure to look for documentation of the specific ligament, as well as laterality. ICD-10-CM also contains code series for:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>M23.60, other spontaneous disruption of unspecified ligament of knee</li>\r\n	<li>M23.62, other spontaneous disruption of posterior cruciate ligament of knee</li>\r\n	<li>M23.64, other spontaneous disruption of lateral collateral ligament of knee</li>\r\n	<li>M23.67, other spontaneous disruption of capsular ligament of knee</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nAlso remember that other spontaneous disruption does not mean unspecified spontaneous disruption. Other means we have the information, but no code. Unspecified means we don’t know because our provider didn’t tell us.\r\n\r\nSpeaking of unspecified, category M23.- includes three unspecified codes:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>M23.90, unspecified internal derangement of unspecified knee</li>\r\n	<li>M23.91, unspecified internal derangement of right knee</li>\r\n	<li>M23.92, unspecified internal derangement of left knee</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nNotice that M23.90 denotes an unspecified derangement of an unspecified knee. If you are reporting that code, you need to have a chat with your provider about basic documentation. Really, the provider should know (and note) which knee he or she examined.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;',
