		'publication' : 'justcoding-website',
		'resource_type' : NULL,
		'title' : 'ICD-10-PCS: Are you in the correct row?',
		'published' : '2012-09-06 09:02:03',
		'status' : 1,
		'summary' : '',
		'body' : '<a href=\"http://blogs.hcpro.com/icd-10/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/TIP1.gif\"><img class=\"alignright  wp-image-2979\" title=\"TIP\" src=\"http://blogs.hcpro.com/icd-10/wp-content/uploads/2012/08/TIP1.gif\" alt=\"\" width=\"143\" height=\"143\" /></a>If you have looked at the ICD-10-PCS Manual, you know that the codes are arranged in tables based on the first three characters of the code. The table contains all of the possible choices for characters four through seven for that particular three-character starting point.\r\n\r\nFor instance, the surgeon is performing an insertion into the subcutaneous tissue of fascia. Your first three characters would be:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>0 for Medical and Surgical section</li>\r\n	<li>J (subcutaneous tissue and fascia) for the body system</li>\r\n	<li>H for the root operation Insertion</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nThe table then gives you the following choices for a body part:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>S, subcutaneous tissue and fascia, head and neck</li>\r\n	<li>T, subcutaneous tissue and fascia, trunk</li>\r\n	<li>V, subcutaneous tissue and fascia, upper extremity</li>\r\n	<li>W, subcutaneous tissue and fascia, lower extremity</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nHowever, T is off in its own row even though all four body parts have the same options for approach and qualifier. Fourth character T, however, has one additional device that is not an option for the other three body parts.\r\n\r\nYou need to pay attention to those distinctions because ICD-10-PCS guidelines state: valid codes include all combinations of choices in characters 4 through 7 contained in the same row of the table.\r\n\r\nSo even though all four body parts are in one table, they are in separate rows.\r\n\r\nAs a result, 0JHT0VZ (insertion of infusion pump into trunk subcutaneous tissue and fascia, open approach) is a valid code, 0JHS0VZ is not.',
