		'summary' : '',
		'body' : 'By now, you probably know that ICD-10-PCS codes contain seven alpha-numeric characters. Each character represents a specific piece of information and those meanings can vary by section.\r\n\r\nIn the Medical and Surgical section of ICD-10-PCS, the fourth character represents the body part. That sounds pretty simple and straightforward, right? You pick the body part that represents the site of the procedure.\r\n\r\nIt is—and it isn’t—that simple. Some of the body parts are very specific, such as right cephalic vein. Others are more general, such as subcutaneous tissue and fascia, abdomen.\r\n\r\nHere are some things to keep in mind when choosing the fourth character for your ICD-10-PCS code:\r\n\r\nIf the provider performs a procedure on a portion of a body part that does not have a separate body part value, code the body part value corresponding to the whole body part. For example, when the provider performs a procedure on the alveolar process of the mandible, you would use  the mandible body part.\r\n\r\nWhere a specific branch of a body part does not have its own body part value, use the closest proximal branch that has a specific body part value. For example, the surgeon destroys part of the trifacial nerve. ICD-10-PCS does not include a specific fourth character for that nerve, so you would code it to the trigeminal nerve.\r\n\r\nSome body parts have a fourth character for procedures performed bilaterally. If the provider performs the exact same procedure on both body parts, for example the fallopian tubes, assign the fourth character for fallopian tubes bilateral. If the body part does not have a bilateral choice, code each procedure separately. For example, a patient undergoes bilateral knee replacement. You would report two procedure codes—one with the fourth character for the right knee, the other with the fourth character for the left knee.\r\n\r\nNot sure what ICD-10-PCS includes in a body part? No problem. ICD-10-PCS includes a body part key to help.\r\n\r\nIf you look up zygomatic process of frontal bone, the key directs you to code the procedure to either frontal bone, right, or frontal bone, left.',
