		'resource_type' : NULL,
		'title' : 'We’re removing veins in ICD-10-PCS',
		'published' : '2012-09-13 11:29:48',
		'status' : 1,
		'summary' : '',
		'body' : 'Today we are taking a peek into OR 3 at the Stitch ‘Em Up Hospital to watch Dr. Cap I. Larry work on some blood vessels. Then we’re going to code her procedure.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://blogs.hcpro.com/icd-10/wp-content/uploads/2012/09/Leg-vein.jpg\"><img class=\"alignright size-medium wp-image-2991\" title=\"Leg vein\" src=\"http://blogs.hcpro.com/icd-10/wp-content/uploads/2012/09/Leg-vein-112x300.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"112\" height=\"300\" /></a>Dr. Larry is harvesting part of the patient’s saphenous vein to use as a graft in heart bypass surgery. In ICD-9-CM, we can’t code the vein harvest as a separate procedure. It is included in the bypass procedure.\r\n\r\nHowever, in ICD-10-PCS, we can code both procedures according to guideline B3.9: “If an autograft is obtained from a different body part in order to complete the objective of the procedure, a separate procedure is coded.”\r\n\r\nSo we know we are in the Medical and Surgical section of ICD-10-PCS, which gives us a first character of 0. We know we are dealing with a lower vein (the saphenous vein is located in the leg), which gives us a second character 6.\r\n\r\nNow we need to determine what root operation Dr. Larry is performing. She is cutting out a portion of the vein, which leads us to root operation, Extraction. That makes our third character B.\r\n\r\nOur code so far then is 06B.\r\n\r\nOn to the table for 06B. In order to select the correct fourth character, we need to know which specific vein (greater or less saphenous) and which side (left or right). Dr. Larry documented greater saphenous of the left leg, which gives us a fourth character of Q.\r\n\r\nWe also need to know which approached Dr. Larry used to harvest the vein:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Open</li>\r\n	<li>Percutaneous</li>\r\n	<li>Percutanous endoscopic</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nAll three are possible choices for the fifth character. In this case, Dr. Larry documented a percutanous endoscopic approach. So our fifth character is 4.\r\n\r\nThe table provides only one option for character 6 (the device), so we know our sixth character is Z.\r\n\r\nThat leaves the seventh character. The table gives us two options:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Diagnostic</li>\r\n	<li>No qualifier</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nWe know the procedure is not diagnostic. Dr. Larry is harvesting a vein, so we’ll use a seventh character Z, no qualifier.\r\n\r\nThat makes our code: 06BQ4ZZ.\r\n\r\nNow, where did that vein go?',
