		'status' : 1,
		'summary' : '',
		'body' : 'We all know coder productivity will go down after the transition to ICD-10 and it may never rebound to current levels. The question is, how much will productivity decline?\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://blogs.hcpro.com/icd-10/wp-content/uploads/2012/10/down-arrow.jpg\"><img class=\"alignright  wp-image-3059\" title=\"down arrow\" src=\"http://blogs.hcpro.com/icd-10/wp-content/uploads/2012/10/down-arrow-300x200.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"245\" height=\"163\" /></a>It could drop more than you expect if preliminary results of a pilot study presented during the AHIMA National Convention are any indication.\r\n\r\nRight now, inpatient coders complete an average of 24 charts each day, according to Susan Fenton, PhD, RHIA, assistant professor of health information management at Texas State University in San Marco. Fenton joined forces with UASI, an HIM consulting firm, and the University of Cincinnati Health, University Hospital to conduct a small study into coder productivity in ICD-9-CM and ICD-10-PCS.\r\n\r\nThe study involved only six coders, so it is not a comprehensive study, Fenton said. Rather than have coders code the same records in ICD-9-CM and ICD-10-PCS, Fenton’s team selected 54 records, then divided the records in half. Coders coded 27 records in ICD-9-CM and 27 different records in ICD-10-PCS. The group selected cases that were as close as possible in complexity and type.\r\n\r\nCoders need an average of 25.51 minutes to code an inpatient record in ICD-9-CM, Fenton said. In ICD-10-PCS, that time jumps to 43.23 minutes, a 69% increase. That number came as a surprise to Fenton and Mary Stanfill, MBI, RHIA, CCS-P, CCS, FAHIMA, vice president of HIM consulting services for UASI.\r\n\r\nThe study team found a huge range in the coders’ productivity. The six coders included took anywhere from an additional 10.6 minutes (31.6%) to 27.78 minutes (89.8%) on average.\r\n\r\nBecause the team is still analyzing the results, they have not yet looked at the accuracy of the code assignment or analyzed how experience and education affect productivity.\r\n\r\nThe study did highlight the importance of training. The difference between the well trained coders and the not-well-trained coders was significant, Stanfill said. “That tells me that training is worth it.”',
