		'body' : '<strong></strong>Hurricane Sandy blasted the Mid-Atlantic region this week, causing plenty of destruction in its wake.  We could undoubtedly spend a lot of time coding for the injuries people suffered as a result of the hurricane/tropical storm—broken bones, contusions, lacerations, and so on.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://blogs.hcpro.com/icd-10/wp-content/uploads/2012/10/hurricane.jpg\"><img class=\"alignright  wp-image-3104\" title=\"hurricane\" src=\"http://blogs.hcpro.com/icd-10/wp-content/uploads/2012/10/hurricane-300x200.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"260\" height=\"173\" /></a>Instead of the actual injuries, let’s look at some of the codes for external causes in ICD-10-CM. You probably know these better as ICD-9-CM E codes. They are the codes that explain how and where the patient suffered an injury.\r\n\r\nICD-10-CM contains a whole series of codes for cataclysmic storm (X37). All of these codes require a seventh character to denote the encounter type:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>A, initial encounter</li>\r\n	<li>D, subsequent encounter</li>\r\n	<li>S, sequela</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nMany also require one or two placeholders (X) so the character for the encounter ends up in the correct place in the code.\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>X37.0, hurricane</li>\r\n	<li>X37.1, tornado</li>\r\n	<li>X37.2, blizzard (snow)(ice)</li>\r\n	<li>X37.3, dust storm</li>\r\n	<li>X37.4, tidalwave</li>\r\n	<li>X37.8, other cataclysmic storm\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Cloudburst</li>\r\n	<li>Torrential rain</li>\r\n	<li>Excludes2: flood (X38)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>X37.9, unspecified cataclysmic storm\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Storm NOS</li>\r\n	<li>Excludes1: collapse of dam or man-made structure causing earth movement (X39.0)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nNotice this series includes both an “other” and an “unspecified” option. Even though ICD-10-CM includes unspecified codes, you should avoid using them as much as possible. One of the main reasons for moving to ICD-10 is for increased specificity. An unspecified code doesn’t give you that additional level of detail.\r\n\r\nThis series of codes also includes both types of Excludes notes.\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>An Excludes1 note means not coded here. Think of this as a pure excludes note. You should never report the excluded code with the code above the Excludes1 note.</li>\r\n	<li>An Excludes2 note means not included here. The condition excluded is not part of the condition under which it is listed, but a patient may have both conditions at the same time. So a patient could have suffered injuries as the result of both a flood and torrential rain. It’s okay to report both.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nYou might also see patients who have been exposed to fire as a result of the hurricane. More than 80 homes in Breezy Point, in New York City\'s Queens borough, burned during the storm.\r\n\r\nICD-10-CM includes codes to denote exposure to both an uncontrolled and a controlled fire. For exposure to uncontrolled fire in building or structure, select the appropriate code from series X00.\r\n\r\nNote that X00 codes also require a seventh character to denote the encounter, so you will need a placeholder again.\r\n\r\nThis series of codes also includes several different notes:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Includes: conflagration in building or structure</li>\r\n	<li>Code first any associated cataclysm</li>\r\n	<li>Excludes2:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Exposure to ignition or melting of nightwear (X05)</li>\r\n	<li>Exposure to ignition or melting of other clothing and apparel (X06-)</li>\r\n	<li>Exposure to other specified smoke, fire and flames (X08.-)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nIf the fire is uncontrolled, but not in a building or structure, choose a code from X01.',
