		'legacy_content_id' : 'W3113',
		'content_type' : 'article',
		'publication' : 'justcoding-website',
		'resource_type' : NULL,
		'title' : 'You\'ll never believe what that crazy coyote did this time',
		'published' : '2012-11-07 07:11:00',
		'status' : 1,
		'summary' : '',
		'body' : 'Wile E. Coyote may bill himself as a Super Genius, but based on his last visit to the ACME ED, I think that’s overstating things a bit.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://blogs.hcpro.com/icd-10/wp-content/uploads/2012/11/tunnel.jpg\"><img class=\"alignright  wp-image-3114\" title=\"tunnel\" src=\"http://blogs.hcpro.com/icd-10/wp-content/uploads/2012/11/tunnel-300x230.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"276\" height=\"211\" /></a>What landed Wile E. back in the ED, you ask? Another complicated, convoluted plan to snag a roadrunner lunch.\r\n\r\nIn this, um, ingenious plan, Wile E. painted a tunnel opening on a hillside to lure his lunch into his clutches. The only problem was, the “meep, meep” he thought meant food actually signaled a really large truck moving at a high rate of speed through Wile E.’s shortcut.\r\n\r\nThings didn’t end well for Wile E.\r\n\r\nThe ACME ambulance crew brought him in and (un)luckily for Wile E. (and for us), Dr. Fudd was on duty.  Dr. Fudd is not our top doc and he’s really bad at documentation.\r\n\r\nLet’s see what Dr. Fudd did document so we can figure out what additional information we need to code Wile E.’s injuries.\r\n\r\nFirst, Wile E. suffered multiple broken bones, which is not surprising since he was run over by a truck. For fractures we need to know:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Specific site (which bone and where on the bone)</li>\r\n	<li>Side (left or right)</li>\r\n	<li>Type of fracture (open or closed, displaced or non-displced)</li>\r\n	<li>Encounter (initial, subsequent, sequela)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nIn reviewing the documentation, we note that Dr. Fudd documented this is an initial visit. That will give us our seventh character extension for the codes that require one.\r\n\r\nWile E.’s list of fractures includes:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Broken leg</li>\r\n	<li>Broken ankle</li>\r\n	<li>Multiple rib fractures</li>\r\n	<li>Multiple foot fractures</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nFirst things first, which side are the fractures on? Keep in mind they can be on different sides, or even on both sides (in which case, we would report two different codes—one for the left side and one for the right).\r\n\r\nDr. Fudd documented that he sent Wile E. for x-rays for left-side fractures. Can we code from that documentation? No. We need Dr. Fudd to either specify that the fractures are on Wile E.’s left side or to document that he reviewed the radiology report of left-sided fractures.\r\n\r\nSo we’ll have query. But before we do, let’s make a list of all of the specific information we need so we only need to send a single query.\r\n\r\nAre Wile E.’s fractures open or closed? Dr. Fudd only documented the ribs as closed fractures, nothing about the leg and foot. That’s something else to add to our query.\r\n\r\nThe <em>2013 ICD-10-CM Official Guidelines for Coding and Reporting</em> do give us a default on the question of open or closed as well as displaced or non-displaced. The guidelines state:\r\n\r\n<em>A fracture not indicated as open or closed should be coded to closed. A fracture not indicated whether displaced or not displaced should be coded to displaced.</em>\r\n\r\nHowever, ICD-10-CM does include specific seventh characters to denote types of open fractures. If we can obtain that information, we should because it will make the coding—and the medical record—more accurate.\r\n\r\nIn response to our query, Dr. Fudd documents the following:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Broken leg—transverse right tibia, shaft, class I Gustilo, displaced</li>\r\n	<li>Broken ankle—right medial malleolus and trimalleolar, both with dislocation, class II Gustilo</li>\r\n	<li>Multiple broken ribs—right side, closed</li>\r\n	<li>Multiple foot fractures—third, fourth, and fifth metatarsal, right foot, closed, non-displaced,</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nThe broken ribs are easy. We only have four choices—single or multiple, right or left. In this case, we would report:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>S22.41XA, multiple fractures of ribs, right side, initial visit</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nOn to the rest of the fractures. By the way, did you notice all of the fractures are on the right side not the left like the x-ray order? It seems Dr. Fudd wrote an incorrect initial x-ray order. Fortunately, the radiologist pointed out the error and Dr. Fudd amended the order. He just didn’t include it in the record. (The radiologist, however, did.)\r\n\r\nFor the ankle and leg fractures, Dr. Fudd notes class I and class II Gustilo. If you don’t regularly work with traumatic fractures or orthopedics, you might not be familiar with the Gustilo-Anderson classification system. The Gustilo-Anderson classification identifies the severity of the soft tissue damage.\r\n\r\nIf you aren’t familiar with it, make sure your physicians are. And make sure they know to document it.\r\n\r\nICD-10-CM includes two different seventh characters for the initial visit of an open fracture:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>B, initial encounter for open fracture type I or II</li>\r\n	<li>C, initial encounter for open fracture type IIIA, IIIB, or IIIC</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nFor the open fractures, we would report:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>S82.421B, displaced transverse fracture of shaft of right fibula, initial encounter for open fracture type I or II</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>S82.51XB, displaced fracture of medial malleolus of right tibia, initial encounter for open fracture type I or II</li>\r\n	<li>S82.851B, displaced trimalleolar fracture of right lower leg, initial encounter for open fracture type I or II</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nNow we’re down to the foot fractures. Wile E. broke three metatarsals, so we need these three codes:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>S92.334A, nondisplaced fracture of third metatarsal bone, right foot, initial encounter</li>\r\n	<li>S92.344A, nondisplaced fracture of fourth metatarsal bone, right foot, initial encounter</li>\r\n	<li>S92.354A, nondisplaced fracture of fifth metatarsal bone, right foot, initial encounter</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nThat’s all for Wile E.’s broken bones. What other injuries did he suffer? According to Dr. Fudd’s  (somewhat sketchy) documentation, Wile E.’s only other injury is a lacerated spleen.\r\n\r\nHow big is the spleen laceration? The size of the laceration will determine which of these codes we report (with the appropriate seventh character to denote the encounter):\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>S36.030, Superficial (capsular) laceration of spleen</li>\r\n	<li>S36.031, Moderate laceration of spleen</li>\r\n	<li>S36.032, Major laceration of spleen</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nThe ICD-10-CM Tabular Index includes these size guidelines to help determine severity of the laceration:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><strong>Superficial—</strong>less than 1 cm</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Moderate</strong>—1 to 3 cm</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Major—</strong>greater than 3 cm</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nDr. Fudd documented a 2.3 cm lacteration, which gives us S36.031A.\r\n\r\nAnd with that, Wile E. hobbles out of the ED to hopefully order some takeout for dinner.',
		'meta_keywords' : '',
