		'title' : 'Have you done your ICD-10 coder assessments?',
		'published' : '2012-11-08 09:16:50',
		'status' : 1,
		'summary' : '',
		'body' : 'Do you know what you don’t know about ICD-10? Do you know where your knowledge gaps are? Unfortunately, the answer is probably no.\r\n\r\nMore than half of the people who responded to our completely unscientific poll on JustCoding said their organizations haven’t performed any coder assessments in preparation for ICD-10.\r\n\r\nI was a little surprised by that, especially when I looked back at the timelines AHIMA and AAPC put out in 2010 and 2011. Those guidelines recommended coders complete anatomy and physiology (A&amp;P) assessments by mid-2011 based on the October 1, 2013 implementation date.\r\n\r\nMove the implementation date forward one year to October 1, 2014, and you can also move those assessment target dates up a year. So coders should have completed assessments by mid-2012. It’s now November and 56% of respondents said their organizations had not yet conducted any coder assessments.\r\n\r\nWhat do you know now? How strong is your A&amp;P knowledge? Granted, human anatomy hasn’t changed in a really long time, but when did you last actually review anatomy? Did you really know it or do you assume you do because you took A&amp;P when you became a coder?\r\n\r\nIf your organization hasn’t done a coder assessment, do one yourself. Identify which body systems you know well and which ones you know the least, recommends <strong>Gloryanne Bryant, BS, RHIA, RHIT, CCS, CDIP, CCDS,</strong> an HIM professional and leader for more than 30 years. Focus your training on your weakest areas, but don’t forget to review your stronger areas as well. Bryant also recommended determining how well you know the current coding guidelines. Most of them are going to stay the same in ICD-10. If you don’t know them now, start learning them. At the very least, review the guidelines. They change almost every year. Again, maybe not a lot, but you still need to stay on top of those changes.\r\n\r\nUntil you know where your knowledge gaps are, you can’t create an education plan. That’s true for individual coders and for organizations as a whole. Without a solid foundation in A&amp;P, medical terminology, and pathophysiology, you won’t succeed in ICD-9, let alone ICD-10.',
