		'status' : 1,
		'summary' : '',
		'body' : 'Most of the odd ICD-10-CM codes, the ones that make us laugh or roll our eyes, live in Chapter 20 (External causes of mortality).\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://blogs.hcpro.com/icd-10/wp-content/uploads/2012/11/deer-with-gun.jpg\"><img class=\"alignright  wp-image-3169\" title=\"deer with gun\" src=\"http://blogs.hcpro.com/icd-10/wp-content/uploads/2012/11/deer-with-gun-288x300.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"227\" height=\"236\" /></a>Here you will find such gems as:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>X32, exposure to sunlight (which does not include tanning beds)</li>\r\n	<li>X52, prolonged stay in weightless environment (I’d love to be weightless)</li>\r\n	<li>W61.43, pecked by turkey (apparently it didn’t want to be Thanksgiving dinner)</li>\r\n	<li>W56.41, bitten by shark (we’re going to need a bigger boat)</li>\r\n	<li>W49.01, hair causing external constriction (keep the scissors handy)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nNot all of the circumstances described by external cause codes are laughing matters.\r\n\r\nYou’ll also find codes such as:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>V00.321, fall from snow-skis (not very funny if you’re the one falling and potentially very painful)</li>\r\n	<li>W40.0, explosion of blasting material (only amusing when animated characters are involved)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nSome of the external cause codes include a remarkable amount of detail and in order to report the correct code, the provider needs to document that detail. Consider code series V30 (occupant of three-wheeled motor vehicle injured in collision with pedestrian or animal).\r\n\r\nYour code choices include:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>V30.0, driver of three-wheeled motor vehicle injured in collision with pedestrian or animal in nontraffic accident</li>\r\n	<li>V30.1, passenger in three-wheeled motor vehicle injured in collision with pedestrian or animal in nontraffic accident</li>\r\n	<li>V30.2, person on outside of three-wheeled motor vehicle injured in collision with pedestrian or animal in nontraffic accident</li>\r\n	<li>V30.3, unspecified occupant of three-wheeled motor vehicle injured in collision with pedestrian or animal in nontraffic accident</li>\r\n	<li>V30.4, person boarding or alighting a three-wheeled motor vehicle injured in collision with pedestrian or animal</li>\r\n	<li>V30.5, driver of three-wheeled motor vehicle injured in collision with pedestrian or animal in traffic accident</li>\r\n	<li>V30.6, passenger in three-wheeled motor vehicle injured in collision with pedestrian or animal in traffic accident</li>\r\n	<li>V30.7, person on outside of three-wheeled motor vehicle injured in collision with pedestrian or animal in traffic accident</li>\r\n	<li>V30.9, unspecified occupant of three-wheeled motor vehicle injured in collision with pedestrian or animal in traffic accident</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nIn order to choose the correct code, you need to know which person was involved (driver, passenger, or someone outside the vehicle) and whether the accident was traffic or non-traffic related. You also need to know the encounter type so you can add the appropriate seventh character (just don’t forget your placeholders).\r\n\r\nSome external cause codes include intent, such as:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>W33.0, accidental rifle, shotgun and larger firearm discharge</li>\r\n	<li>W33.1, accidental rifle, shotgun and larger firearm malfunction</li>\r\n	<li>X73, intentional self-harm by rifle, shotgun and larger firearm discharge</li>\r\n	<li>X94.1, assault by hunting rifle</li>\r\n	<li>Y23.1, hunting rifle discharge, undetermined intent</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nICD-10-CM does not yet include a code for shot by an angry, vengeful deer. But who knows? We have lots of room to expand ICD-10-CM. Until then, happy hunting (in your code book)!',
