		'published' : '2013-06-28 11:36:03',
		'status' : 1,
		'summary' : '',
		'body' : 'Curious to know what changes the four cooperating parties made to the ICD-10-CM codes for 2014? You can now find out by downloading the 2014 ICD-10-CM codes from the <a href=\"http://www.cdc.gov/nchs/icd/icd10cm.htm\">Centers for Disease Control and Prevention</a> (CDC) and <a href=\"http://www.cms.gov/Medicare/Coding/ICD10/2014-ICD-10-CM-and-GEMs-.html\">CMS</a> <a href=\"http://blogs.hcpro.com/icd-10/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/news01.jpg\"><img class=\"alignright size-medium wp-image-3371\" alt=\"news01\" src=\"http://blogs.hcpro.com/icd-10/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/news01-300x193.jpg\" width=\"210\" height=\"135\" /></a>websites. The updated coding guidelines for ICD-10-CM are not available yet.\r\n\r\nMany of the changes for 2014 are editorial changes. For example, the cooperating parties changed “Table of drugs and chemicals” to “Table of Drugs and Chemicals\".\r\n\r\nIn the Index of External causes, the listings for misadventure during surgical or medical care (Y69) no longer direct coders to the term “misadventure” for non-drug related injuries. Instead, coders are directed to the Index to Diseases and Injuries, Complication(s).\r\n\r\nIn the Alphabetic Index, coders will find a significant number of changes in the pregnancy section.\r\n\r\nTo quickly locate all of the changes, download Addenda D and E, which show all of the changes to the Alphabetic Index (Addenda D) and Index of External Causes (Addenda E).\r\n\r\nThe CDC and CMS previously released the ICD-10-PCS updates for 2014 in May.',
		'meta_keywords' : '',
