		'body' : 'Dashing through the snow, in a one-horse open sleigh … oh, wait, maybe that’s not such a good idea.\r\n\r\nLittle Bobby came down with chilblains, while Suzie developed frostbite.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://blogs.hcpro.com/icd-10/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/Sleigh-ride.jpg\"><img class=\"alignright size-medium wp-image-3716\" alt=\"Sleigh ride\" src=\"http://blogs.hcpro.com/icd-10/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/Sleigh-ride-300x214.jpg\" width=\"300\" height=\"214\" /></a>ICD-10-CM only gives us one choice for chilblains, T69.1, but we need two placeholders and a seventh character to identify the encounter. So the code for an initial encounter for chilblains is T69.1XXA (Note that it doesn’t matter if you capitalize the Xs or any other letters in the code).\r\n\r\nCoding for frostbite is a little more complicated. We need to know where, specifically, the frostbite is located. In Suzie’s case, she was zipping along in an open sleigh, so her frostbite is on her face. Her mother bundled up every other part of Suzie.\r\n\r\nWe also need to know if the frostbite is superficial or if tissue necrosis has occurred.\r\n\r\nFortunately, for Suzie, her frostbite is superficial and limited to her right ear, nose, and forehead. This is her first visit, so we would code:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>T33.011A, superficial frostbite of right ear, initial encounter</li>\r\n	<li>T33.02XA, superficial frostbite of nose, initial encounter</li>\r\n	<li>T33.09XA, superficial frostbite of other part of head, initial encounter</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nMake sure you don’t forget the placeholders on the nose and other part of the head codes.\r\n\r\nNo more sleigh rides. We’ll stay home by the fire, roasting chestnuts. Great plan until the chestnuts explode (I guess we over-roasted them) and the fire spreads out of control.\r\n\r\nThe resulting injuries include burns to the thumb and first three fingers of the left hand (from grabbing the hot chestnuts), bruises to various body parts from chestnut projectiles, and one unlucky spectator whose glass shattered after a direct hit from a chestnut, causing lacerations to the hand.\r\n\r\nICD-10-CM very helpfully divides burns to the fingers into:<a href=\"http://blogs.hcpro.com/icd-10/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/Fireplace.jpg\"><img class=\"alignright size-full wp-image-3717\" alt=\"Fireplace\" src=\"http://blogs.hcpro.com/icd-10/wp-content/uploads/2013/12/Fireplace.jpg\" width=\"288\" height=\"230\" /></a>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Thumb</li>\r\n	<li>Single finger excluding thumb</li>\r\n	<li>Multiple fingers including the thumb</li>\r\n	<li>Multiple fingers excluding the thumb</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nIn this case, we would report:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>T23.142A, burn of first degree of multiple left fingers (nail), including thumb, initial encounter</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nWe also need to use additional external cause code to identify the source, place, and intent of the burn (X00-X19, X75-X77, X96-X98, Y92):\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>X10.1XXA, contact with hot food, initial encounter</li>\r\n	<li>Y92.018, other place in single-family (private) house as the place of occurrence of the external cause</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nX75-X77 denote intentional self-harm, while X96-98 specify assault. Although we were assaulted by hot chestnuts, I don’t think we can say the chestnuts meant to do it.\r\n\r\nFor our contusions, we would report a separate code for each body part bruised, such as:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>S00.83XA, contusion of other part of head (forehead)</li>\r\n	<li>S40.022A, contusion of left upper arm, initial encounter</li>\r\n	<li>S70.11XA, contusion of right thigh</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nFinally, our unfortunate guest with the broken glass. We need to know which hand was injured, whether any of the glass remained in the wound, and the encounter. Remember that if the finger(s) or wrist is lacerated as well, we would report additional codes.\r\n\r\nFor a laceration of the right hand without a foreign body in the wound, initial encounter, we would report S61.411A. If it’s the left hand, we would report S61.412A. We do have a code for unspecified hand, but the physician really should be documenting laterality.\r\n\r\nNow that we’ve ushered out the injured, it’s time to clean up this mess so we can plan our next holiday gathering.',
