		'status' : 1,
		'summary' : '',
		'body' : 'Our friends from the <a href=\"http://acdis.org/\">Association of Clinical Documentation Improvement Specialists</a> came back from the desert with some minor maladies. Apparently everything that happens in Vegas doesn’t stay in Vegas, it ends up at Fix ‘Em Up Clinic.\r\n\r\nPoor Melissa is seriously exhausted after spending a week overseeing the conference (and enjoying the Vegas attractions). Not to mention all of the work she put in before the conference.\r\n\r\nDr. Presley diagnoses fatigue. We really need to work on his documentation skills.\r\n\r\nTo code Melissa’s fatigue, we need to know the type. The ICD-10-CM Alphabetic Index lists 14 different terms under Fatigue. That doesn’t mean we have 14 different code choices. Four of the terms give us F48.8 (other specified nonpsychotic mental disorders) and two direct us to other conditions.\r\n\r\nGeneral fatigue falls under R53.83 (other fatigue) and includes the terms:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Fatigue NOS</li>\r\n	<li>Lack of energy</li>\r\n	<li>Lethargy</li>\r\n	<li>Tiredness</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nTake a look a little higher up in the Tabular List under R53.8 (other malaise and fatigue). You’ll notice a nice long list of excluded conditions. This is an Excludes1 note, which means you cannot code the two conditions together. One of those excluded conditions is exhaustion and fatigue due to excessive exertion (T73.3).\r\n\r\nSo we need to closely look at Dr. Presley’s documentation to see whether he diagnosed general fatigue or fatigue due to excessive exertion. We may need to query to be sure.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://blogs.hcpro.com/icd-10/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/CatwStomachAche.jpg\"><img class=\"alignright size-full wp-image-3340\" alt=\"CatwStomachAche\" src=\"http://blogs.hcpro.com/icd-10/wp-content/uploads/2013/03/CatwStomachAche.jpg\" width=\"193\" height=\"250\" /></a>ACDIS member chick Penny didn’t fare well at the conference either. She came back with a nasty stomach bug.\r\n\r\nDr. Presley documents “stomach flu.” If we look up stomach in the ICD-10-CM Alphabetic Index, we find a note to see condition.\r\n\r\nLet’s try flu instead. We do have a code for intestinal flu, not elsewhere classified (A08.4). However, our CDI friends point out that stomach flu isn’t really the flu at all. It’s gastroenteritis. ICD-10-CM has lots of codes for gastroenteritis, depending on the cause. So we’re going to query Dr. Presley to find out whether he means intestinal flu or gastroenteritis. If it’s gastroenteritis, we need the cause.\r\n\r\nThe gastroenteritis codes fall into two different sections of ICD-10-CM codes, depending on what caused the condition:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>A, certain infectious and parasitic diseases</li>\r\n	<li>K, diseases of the digestive system</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nIn Penny’s case, Dr. Presley documents gastroenteritis due to norovirus, which leads us to A08.11 (acute gastroenteropathy due to Norwalk agent).\r\n\r\nI think I’ll skip the buffet the next time I’m in Vegas.',
