		'title' : 'Congenital anomaly coding at the carnival sideshow ',
		'published' : '2014-10-21 11:08:46',
		'status' : 1,
		'summary' : '',
		'body' : 'If you are a fan of American Horror Story (I’m not) or carnival sideshows (again, not my thing, but I’m not judging), you’ve seen some odd creatures. Maybe you’ve wondered if they are real. After all, P.T. Barnum once tried to pass off a monkey body sewn onto a fish as a Feejee mermaid.\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_4119\" align=\"alignright\" width=\"123\"]<a href=\"http://blogs.hcpro.com/icd-10/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Feejee_mermaid-2.jpg\"><img class=\"size-medium wp-image-4119\" alt=\"&quot;Feejee mermaid&quot; by Original uploader was Chris 73 at en.wikipedia - Originally from en.wikipedia; description page is/was here.. Licensed under Public domain via Wikimedia Commons - http://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Feejee_mermaid.jpg#mediaviewer/File:Feejee_mermaid.jpg\" src=\"http://blogs.hcpro.com/icd-10/wp-content/uploads/2014/10/Feejee_mermaid-2-123x300.jpg\" width=\"123\" height=\"300\" /></a> \"Feejee mermaid\" by Original uploader  Chris 73 at en.wikipedia - Licensed under Public domain via Wikimedia Commons [/caption]\r\n\r\nIn the case of American Horror Story, some of the “freaks” are based on people who suffered from actual medical conditions.\r\n\r\nTake, for example, the bearded lady. Most women have some facial hair (otherwise we wouldn’t need all of the beauty products promising to do away with the unsightly stuff). However, some women have it worse than most of us. They actually end up with a beard or mustache. This can be the result of the genetic disorder hypertrichosis.\r\n\r\nIn ICD-10-CM, codes for hypertrichosis appear in three different sections.\r\n\r\nThe first category, L68 (hypertrichosis), includes excess hair. However, the Excludes1 note tells us that we cannot code these conditions in a patient with hypertrichosis:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Congenital hypertrichosis (Q84.2)</li>\r\n	<li>Persistent lanugo (Q84.2)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nExcludes1 means mutually exclusive. You can’t have the two conditions together.\r\n\r\nCategory L68 includes the following subcategories:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>L68.0, hirsutism</li>\r\n	<li>L68.1, acquired hypertrichosis lanuginosa</li>\r\n	<li>L68.2, localized hypertrichosis</li>\r\n	<li>L68.3, polytrichia</li>\r\n	<li>L68.8, other hypertrichosis</li>\r\n	<li>L68.9, hypertrichosis, unspecified</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nWe’ve already mentioned the second place hypertrichosis codes appear: Q84.2 (other congenital malformations of hair).\r\n\r\nThe final set of hypertrichosis codes appears in subcategory H02.86 (hypertrichosis of eyelid). The codes are divided by the upper and lower eyelid, as well as laterality.\r\n\r\nAnother performer in the freak show is lobster boy. Real or fake? Actually, it’s a real condition. In the mid-1900s, Grady Franklin Stiles Jr., suffered from ectrodactyly, in which the fingers and toes are fused together.\r\n\r\nIf you look up ectrodactyly in the ICD-10-CM Alphabetic Index, you won’t find the condition. You can find it in the ICD-9-CM Alphabetic Index with notes that tell you to see “absence, finger, congenital” and “absence, toe, congenital.”\r\n\r\nIf we look up “absence, finger” in the ICD-10-CM Alphabetic Index we find two choices:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Acquired, Z89.02-</li>\r\n	<li>Congenital – See Agenesis, hand</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nAgenesis is simply the failure of a body part to develop. Unfortunately, quite a few body parts can fail to develop, judging by the list of subterms under Agenesis in the ICD-10-CM Alphabetic Index.\r\n\r\nFor agenesis of the hand, ICD-10-CM includes the nonessential modifiers “and fingers,” “complete,” and “partial.” Nonessential modifiers are just that—nonessential. So you use the same code even if the physician doesn’t document those modifying terms.\r\n\r\nWe have four code choices based on laterality:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Q71.30, congenital absence of unspecified hand and finger</li>\r\n	<li>Q71.31, congenital absence of right hand and finger</li>\r\n	<li>Q71.32, congenital absence of left hand and finger</li>\r\n	<li>Q71.33, congenital absence of hand and finger, bilateral</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nICD-10-CM does include an entry for “lobster-claw hand.” It leads you to code Q71.6- (lobster-claw hand). Here’s where physician documentation will really be important. If the physician documents “lobster-claw hand,” use the Q71.6- codes (with an additional digit to specify laterality). If the physician documents “agenesis” or “congenital absence of fingers,” just the Q71.3-.\r\n\r\nYou can spend a lot of time online searching for the distinctions between the two and you’ll even find “cleft hand,” which creates even more confusion. If you are unsure which condition the patient has based on the documentation, you can always query the physician.\r\n\r\nOur final freak show example was commonly referred to as Pinhead. These curiosities were usually people who suffered from microcephaly, a neurodevelopmental disorder that causes abnormal growth of the brain.\r\n\r\nThis condition is pretty easy to code. We have one choice in ICD-10-CM: Q02 (microcephaly), which also includes hydromicrocephaly and micrencephalon.',
