		'body' : 'Ever play with a Magic 8 Ball? (If not, there’s an app for that.) Ask it a question, shake it up, and get an answer. Usually something vague (and vaguely ominous) like, “Reply hazy try again.”\r\n\r\nAsking whether ICD-10 will indeed (finally) be implemented October 1, 2015, feels a little like asking a Magic 8 Ball.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://blogs.hcpro.com/icd-10/wp-content/uploads/2013/05/Cadusius.jpg\"><img class=\"alignright size-medium wp-image-3449\" src=\"http://blogs.hcpro.com/icd-10/wp-content/uploads/2013/05/Cadusius-300x300.jpg\" alt=\"Cadusius\" width=\"300\" height=\"300\" /></a>The AMA is continuing its efforts to kill ICD-10 outright (at the same time it is trying to make money on training for ICD-10). In an address to the AMA’s House of Delegates November 9, Robert M. Wah, MD, president of the American Medical Society, once again showed how little physicians (at least those in leadership positions at physician societies) understand ICD-10.\r\n\r\nIn his remarks, Wah hyped the increased number of codes as a reason not to go to ICD-10. Sue Bowman, RHIA, CCS, senior director of coding policy and compliance for AHIMA in Chicago<a href=\"http://blogs.hcpro.com/icd-10/2014/08/increased-specificity-leads-to-better-coding/\">, has pretty much blown that complaint out of the water</a>.\r\n\r\nAnd really, why does he care how many codes there are? We’re not asking physicians to code (please, stick to treating patients). We just want them to document what they did.\r\n\r\nWah also dragged out the tried-and-true “sucked into a jet engine” code complaint. Really? That’s the best you can do? An external cause code that is NOT required? How about the ability to tell which leg the patient broke? Probably a little more important–not only to physicians and payers--but also to any physician who treats that patient down the road.\r\n\r\nWant to improve the practice of medicine? Better data will help. Knowing that a particular injury is occurring more often, or a certain treatment works better, or even that more patients suffer delayed healing with a specific type of device will help physicians better treat patients, which is what they claim they want to do.\r\n\r\nSadly, Wah is not alone in his loathing for ICD-10. Right now, 24 members of Congress are physicians or members of the doctors’ caucus, according to Margarita Valdez, director of Congressional relations for AHIMA.\r\n\r\nThat group is solidly on board with Wah and the AMA, and firmly against ICD-10.\r\n\r\nAnd then we have Congress. Two bills to kill ICD-10 are still floating around and Valdez expects them to be reintroduced sometime after Congress convenes with its new session in January. Again, Congress members have no idea what ICD-10 is and isn’t and no idea why it’s better than the system we’ve been using for the past 30 years.\r\n\r\nHave I mentioned ICD-9-CM doesn’t have a code for Ebola? Funny how that disease keeps popping up. Wah may be proud of the AMA’s ability to delay ICD-10 for 10 years, but I’m not impressed. All the AMA is doing is <a href=\"http://blogs.hcpro.com/icd-10/2011/02/icd-10-factoid/\">putting us further behind</a> and holding back the practice of medicine. Make sure your voice is heard. <a href=\"http://www.house.gov/representatives/find/\">Bombard your members of Congress</a>. Trumpet positive ICD-10 messages at your organization.\r\n\r\nLet’s be the squeaky wheel and see if we can finally catch up with the rest of the world.',
