		'body' : 'I’m almost afraid to read my email these days. It seems like every day brings a new group trying to delay ICD-10 or another piece of legislation that ICD-10 opponents might slip delay language into.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://blogs.hcpro.com/icd-10/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/guy-with-question-marks-2.jpg\"><img class=\"alignright size-medium wp-image-3880\" src=\"http://blogs.hcpro.com/icd-10/wp-content/uploads/2014/04/guy-with-question-marks-2-300x225.jpg\" alt=\"guy with question marks (2)\" width=\"300\" height=\"225\" /></a>Multiple physician groups are campaigning for an additional two-year delay to push ICD-10 implementation to 2017.\r\n\r\nAHIMA, the Coalition for ICD-10, and AAPC, among others, are trying to mobilize a \"keep ICD-10 on track\" effort, calling on healthcare professionals to contact their members of Congress and lobby for no more delays.\r\n\r\n<strong>What to watch:</strong> Congress is in a lame-duck session for the rest of the year. The new Congress will be seated in January. Before then, however, Congress will likely vote on a $157 billion departments of Labor-Health and Human Services-Education spending bill. The bill would finance the departments for fiscal year 2015, which started in October.\r\n\r\nThe AMA, its regional societies, and delegations are reportedly working with Reps. Pete Sessions, R-Texas, chair of the House Rules Committee, and Fred Upton, R-Mich., chair of the House Energy and Commerce Committee, to add language to push out ICD-10 implementation by two years.\r\n\r\nThe language is not a done deal, though, and passage of the bill isn’t a sure thing either. It’s been bogged down in committee for six months.\r\n\r\nIf the AMA does not succeed with this appropriations bill, it will likely push hard to have two bills to kill ICD-10 reintroduced. Another Republican Texas representative, Ted Poe, introduced one of those bills, HR 1701, the Cutting Costly Codes Act, in April 2013. The other, S.972, the Cutting Costly Codes Act, was introduced in the Senate by Thomas Coburn, R-Okla., also in 2013. Republicans introduced both bills and the Republicans won control of Congress in the 2014 mid-term elections. However, they may not have enough support to get either bill out of committee.\r\n\r\n<!--more-->And last, but certainly not least, is the sustainable growth rate (SGR) patch. We all remember what happened <a href=\"http://blogs.hcpro.com/icd-10/2014/03/house-passes-bill-that-includes-icd-10-delay/\">with that bill in March</a>.\r\n\r\n<strong>What to remember</strong>: The AMA is the loudest lobbying group opposed to ICD-10. That doesn’t mean it’s the only group. It’s just the most visible one.\r\n\r\nThe other thing to keep in mind is that the AMA only represents approximately 30% of physicians. The other 70% are not members. While it’s easy to think most physicians don’t support ICD-10 because AMA is trying to kill it, that’s not necessarily the case.\r\n\r\n<strong>What we can do</strong>: AHIMA, AAPC, and the Coalition for ICD-10 are urging members to talk to their members of Congress, face-to-face if possible, and explain why we need ICD-10. (<a href=\"http://capwiz.com/ahima/callalert/index.tt?alertid=63889341\">Find your members of Congress here</a>.)\r\n\r\nIf you can’t (or just don’t want to) talk to your Congressional representatives, try some grassroots efforts in your own organization. Talk to your physicians, billers, coders, managers, case managers, CDI staff, HIM staff, C suite (if you can) and make sure your organization is on board. If they are, great. If they aren’t, educate and advocate.\r\n\r\nLet’s be as loud for ICD-10 as AMA has been against it.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;',
