		'legacy_content_id' : 'W4197',
		'content_type' : 'article',
		'publication' : 'justcoding-website',
		'resource_type' : NULL,
		'title' : 'Oh, look, a bird in a tree',
		'published' : '2014-12-08 14:20:44',
		'status' : 1,
		'summary' : '',
		'body' : 'On the first day of Christmas, my true love gave to me, a partridge in a pear tree. How…nice.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://blogs.hcpro.com/icd-10/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/Partridge-in-a-pear-tree.jpg\"><img class=\"alignright size-medium wp-image-4198\" src=\"http://blogs.hcpro.com/icd-10/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/Partridge-in-a-pear-tree-178x300.jpg\" alt=\"Partridge in a pear tree\" width=\"178\" height=\"300\" /></a>Fortunately, the tree is way too big for the living room (it also clashes with my real Christmas tree). The pear tree is potted, so out it goes to the patio.\r\n\r\nUnfortunately, Mr. Whiskers spotted the partridge before I could get the pear tree out of the house. Mr. Whiskers thinks the bird is his Christmas present. (Not that he should get presents. He’s been a bad kitty.)\r\n\r\nMr. Whiskers prepared a sneak attack on his presumed snack, but the partridge was prepared. It launched a barrage of pears at the cat as he attempted to climb the tree. (The bird couldn’t have just relocated?)\r\n\r\nSadly the bird’s aim was a little off (which is only to be expected when one is hurling pears with talons) and Mr. Whiskers escaped unscathed (but motivated to devise a new plan). One of the projectile pears did find a target—it hit my true love right between the eyes. Oh, honey, that looked like it hurt. (Maybe the bird’s aim isn’t so bad after all.)\r\n\r\nMy true love suffered a contusion of the forehead. In ICD-10-CM, we would report S00.83XA (contusion of other part of head) for the initial encounter. You’ll notice the placeholder X to make sure the seventh character is in the seventh position. It doesn’t matter if you capitalize the X or not when you report the code on the claim.\r\n\r\nYou’ll also notice the code description states, “other part of the head.” Underneath the code are these two included conditions:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Bruise of other part of head</li>\r\n	<li>Hematoma of other part of head</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nOther part of the head does not mean this is an unspecified code. We know the part of the head involved. We just don’t have a code for it. This is a “not elsewhere classified” code, not a “not otherwise specified” code.\r\n\r\n<!--more-->ICD-10-CM does include unspecified codes and in some cases you are perfectly justified in using them. Just don’t report S00.90- (unspecified superficial injury of unspecified part of head). If the physician can’t document the type of injury and the location, the payer is probably not going to reimburse you for treatment. Odds are, physicians are already documenting location and type of injury. We may just need to dig a little to find it.\r\n\r\nFor a head injury, even a bruise from being hit by a pear, we should also look for any associated fracture and/or brain injury, such as a concussion. My true love got off easy. The bird doesn’t have Nolan Ryan’s arm, er, talon strength.\r\n\r\nWe can also assign some additional external cause codes. You don’t need to report external cause codes for every case. You only need them if the payer requires them. If you don’t report external cause codes now, you won’t report them in ICD-10-CM.\r\n\r\nFor my true love’s run in with his present, we could add:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>W20.8XXA, other cause of strike by thrown, projected or falling object, initial encounter (you could also consider Y00.XXXA, assault by blunt object, initial encounter. After all, the bird was throwing pears with a purpose.)</li>\r\n	<li>Y92.017, garden or yard in single-family (private) house as the place of occurrence of the external cause (the patio is part of the yard at our house)</li>\r\n	<li>Y99.8, other external cause status</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nMaybe that will teach him not to bring a bird into a cat’s house.',
