		'body' : 'On the second day of Christmas my true love gave to me, two turtle doves.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://blogs.hcpro.com/icd-10/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/Two-turtle-doves.jpg\"><img class=\"alignright size-medium wp-image-4201\" src=\"http://blogs.hcpro.com/icd-10/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/Two-turtle-doves-180x300.jpg\" alt=\"Two turtle doves\" width=\"180\" height=\"300\" /></a>Hmm, you think he would have learned his lesson with the partridge. Apparently not. And apparently Mr. Whiskers isn’t hungry for doves. He barely spared them a glance. He’s just staring out the window at the partridge.\r\n\r\nPerhaps my true love is going for the symbolic with this gift. Turtle doves mate for life.\r\n\r\nWell, they are kind of cute, but the cuddling is getting a little out of hand. So is that turr-turr sound they make.\r\n\r\nMy true love decided he should feed the doves because nothing takes the mind off cuddling like food. (At least in my true love’s opinion.)\r\n\r\nWhat do turtle doves eat? Seeds. And there are now seed pods all over the floor. Here you go, true love, a broom and dust pan to clean up after the birds.\r\n\r\n<!--more-->Maybe expecting my true love to clean up wasn’t such a good idea. The doves apparently don’t love him. In fact, they’re spitting seeds at him. One, make that two, just landed in his eye.\r\n\r\nNow in addition to sporting a large bruise on his head from the partridge’s projectile pear, he also has a scratched cornea courtesy of his lovey-dovey birds.\r\n\r\nIf you look up “scratch” in the ICD-10-CM Alphabetic Index, it directs you to see abrasion. Abrasion of the cornea leads us to code S05.0- (injury of conjunctiva and corneal abrasion without foreign body). That dash tells us the code requires additional characters. Any ideas what those characters could represent?\r\n\r\nIf you said laterality, you win a turtle dove. (Please take them before the cat gets bored watching the partridge and decides the doves will do instead.)\r\n\r\nICD-10-CM includes three code choices under S05.0-:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>S05.00-, injury of conjunctiva and corneal abrasion without foreign body, unspecified eye</li>\r\n	<li>S05.01-, injury of conjunctiva and corneal abrasion without foreign body, right eye</li>\r\n	<li>S05.02-, injury of conjunctiva and corneal abrasion without foreign body, left eye</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nWe’ll also need an X placeholder and a seventh character to denote the encounter as:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>A, initial encounter</li>\r\n	<li>D, subsequent encounter</li>\r\n	<li>S, sequela</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nYou may also have noticed the Excludes1 note under S05.0-:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Foreign body in conjunctival sac (T15.1)</li>\r\n	<li>Foreign body in cornea (T15.0)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nIf my true love wasn’t smart enough to remove the seeds from his eye before going to the doctor, we would use one of the T codes (which also require laterality and a seventh character).\r\n\r\nI can hardly wait to see what he brings tomorrow. It better not be more birds unless they’re dinner.',
