		'body' : 'On the fourth day of Christmas my true love gave to me four calling birds.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://blogs.hcpro.com/icd-10/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/Four-calling-birds.jpg\"><img class=\"alignright size-medium wp-image-4224\" src=\"http://blogs.hcpro.com/icd-10/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/Four-calling-birds-206x300.jpg\" alt=\"Four calling birds\" width=\"206\" height=\"300\" /></a>I’m starting to think he raided a pet shop. Or maybe he captured these in the park. He says they’re calling birds. They look more like blackbirds to me.\r\n\r\nAnd they act like blackbirds. Right now they are fighting for the prime nesting spot in my Christmas tree. More alarmingly, Mr. Whiskers has abandoned his partridge vigil to try and catch the calling birds.\r\n\r\nMy true love better put a stop to that, but alas, numbers more than made up for the size disparity, especially when Mr. Whiskers turned on my true love.\r\n\r\nIn an effort to flee his feathered and feline attackers, my true love tripped over the coffee table. He made a valiant effort to keep his balance, but just before he could completely right himself, he crashed into the glass sliding door to the patio. Make that crashed <em>through</em> the glass sliding door.\r\n\r\nMy true love lives a charmed life, however, and suffered only lacerations from the glass. How he managed that, I will never know.\r\n\r\nHow would we code his misfortune this time? ICD-10-CM groups injuries by body area instead of type of injury. So we can’t turn to a category of codes and find all of the laceration codes. Instead, we’ll find lacerations grouped with all of the other injuries to the hand or leg or whichever body part is affected.\r\n\r\nFor example, my true love suffered lacerations to his right forearm (thankfully he missed the big arteries). We would look up laceration, forearm in the ICD-10-CM Alphabetic Index. If you look up laceration, arm, the index specifies upper arm.\r\n\r\n<!--more-->We need some additional information to report the appropriate code. First is laterality (you’re shocked, I know). Next we need to know if any foreign body remained in the wound. ICD-10-CM includes separate codes for with and without foreign body.\r\n\r\nIf my true love had some lacerations with foreign body and some without, we would report different codes:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>S51.811A, laceration without foreign body of right forearm, initial encounter</li>\r\n	<li>S51.821A, laceration with foreign body of right forearm, initial encounter</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nMake sure you don’t forget the seventh character. S51.811 is not a valid ICD-10-CM code. The seventh character denotes the encounter, and for laceration codes we have three choices:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>A, initial encounter</li>\r\n	<li>D, subsequent encounter</li>\r\n	<li>S, sequela</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nSome antiseptic and Band-Aids should fix my true love right up and he can clean up the mess he (and the birds and the cat) made.',
