		'body' : 'On the fifth day of Christmas my true love gave to me five golden rings. Hey wait, there are only four rings here. Where did the other one go?\r\n\r\nOh no, little Andrew shoved it up his nose.<a href=\"http://blogs.hcpro.com/icd-10/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/Five-gold-rings.jpg\"><img class=\"alignright size-medium wp-image-4227\" src=\"http://blogs.hcpro.com/icd-10/wp-content/uploads/2014/12/Five-gold-rings-163x300.jpg\" alt=\"Five gold rings\" width=\"163\" height=\"300\" /></a>\r\n\r\nTime to remove the ring from the child’s nose and then disinfect it (kid boogers—gross).\r\n\r\nIf we are removing something in ICD-10-PCS, which root operation would we use? (Keep in mind, ICD-10-PCS is really for inpatient procedures. Outpatient facilities and physicians will still use CPT®. But this is a fun exercise.)\r\n\r\nICD-10-PCS does feature root operation Removal. Fortunately for Andrew, pulling a ring out of his nose does not meet the ICD-10-PCS definition of Removal. In ICD-10-PCS, we only use Removal for taking out or off a device from a body part. No device, no Removal.\r\n\r\nWhat other root operations could it be? Extraction perhaps? ICD-10-PCS defines Extraction as “pulling or stripping out or off all or a portion of a body part by the use of force.” That ring is not a body part so we can eliminate Extraction.\r\n\r\nHow about Extirpation? I’ve always wanted to code Extirpation. The ICD-10-PCS definition of Extirpation is “taking or cutting out solid matter from a body part.” The ring is solid matter (at least it better be).\r\n\r\nThe ICD-10-PCS Reference Manual provides the following additional information about Extirpation:\r\n\r\n<em>The solid matter may be an abnormal byproduct of a biological function or a foreign body; it may be imbedded in a body part or in the lumen of a tubular body part. The solid matter may or may not have been previously broken into pieces.</em>\r\n\r\nWinner! Extirpation it is. Our table in ICD-10-PCS is 09C.\r\n\r\n<!--more-->When we look at that table, we see we have a lot of choices for the body part:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Nasal turbinate</li>\r\n	<li>Nasopharynx</li>\r\n	<li>Mastoid sinus, right</li>\r\n	<li>Mastoid sinus, left</li>\r\n	<li>Nasal septum</li>\r\n	<li>Accessory sinus</li>\r\n	<li>Maxillary sinus, right</li>\r\n	<li>Maxillary sinus, left</li>\r\n	<li>Frontal sinus, right</li>\r\n	<li>Frontal sinus, left</li>\r\n	<li>Ethmoid sinus, right</li>\r\n	<li>Ethmoid sinus, left</li>\r\n	<li>Sphenoid sinus, right</li>\r\n	<li>Sphenoid sinus, left</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nWe also have a nice, generic body part, nose (K). Guess which one we’re going to use. Yep, the nice generic nose. Why? Well, we know from anatomy class that Andrew could not have shoved the ring into his sinuses.\r\n\r\nHe could possibly have pushed the ring back into his nasopharynx (the part of the pharynx above the soft palate that is continuous with the nasal passages). But when you think about what the physician will be doing, nose is the best choice.\r\n\r\nThat gives us 09CK as the first four characters of our code.\r\n\r\nOn to the approach. We have four possibilities:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>0, open</li>\r\n	<li>3, percutaneous</li>\r\n	<li>4, percutaneous endoscopic</li>\r\n	<li>X, external</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nOur lives would be much easier if the physician would say, “I used a percutaneous approach.” But they probably won’t, so we need to know what is involved with each approach and look for key words in the documentation.\r\n\r\nIf the doctor is pulling out a ring from Andrew’s nose, he or she is most likely using an external approach.\r\n\r\nICD-10-PCS Coding Guideline B5.3a states that procedures performed within an orifice on structures that are visible without the aid of any instrumentation are coded to approach value X.\r\n\r\nFor percutaneous and percutaneous endoscopic approaches, the physician makes an incision or punctures the skin. An open approach requires cutting through skin. If the physician is using a pair of really long tweezers to pull out the ring, external is the best choice.\r\n\r\nOur final two characters are easy because we only have one choice for each: no device and no qualifier.\r\n\r\nThat makes the final code 09CKXZZ (Extirpation of matter from nose, external approach).\r\n\r\nNow that Andrew is all taken care of and the ring is disinfected, I’m going to put it with the others to have a nice matched set. Only I can’t find the other rings. If those birds took them, they’re dinner!',
