		'body' : '<a href=\"http://blogs.hcpro.com/icd-10/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/Penguin-with-shovel.jpg\"><img class=\"alignright size-medium wp-image-4288\" src=\"http://blogs.hcpro.com/icd-10/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/Penguin-with-shovel-300x264.jpg\" alt=\"Penguin with shovel\" width=\"300\" height=\"264\" /></a>Here in Anytown we are getting blasted by a big winter storm, which means we’re also seeing lots of patients with storm-related injuries at the Fix ‘Em Up Clinic.\r\n\r\nDoug came into the clinic complaining of pain and weakness when lifting his right arm. He was out shoveling the snow using the tried-and-true lift, jerk, and fling method. During one of his tosses, he felt a sharp pain in his shoulder and started having trouble lifting his arm. Dr. Frosty examines Doug and diagnoses a torn rotator cuff.\r\n\r\nDo we have enough information to code Doug’s injury in ICD-10-CM? If we look up tear, rotator cuff, in the ICD-10-CM Alphabetic Index, we find out very quickly that we need more information. Was this a traumatic tear?\r\n\r\nIt’s tempting to say yes right off the bat because Dr. Frosty documented that the injury occurred while Doug was shoveling snow. You can tear you rotator cuff by lifting something too heavy with a jerking motion. However, the majority of rotator cuff tears result from a wearing down of the tendon over time. In his chart, Doug’s age is listed as 57, so we could be looking at a nontraumatic tear.\r\n\r\n<!--more-->Let’s take a look at the rest of Dr. Frosty’s documentation to see if we can find any indication of whether Doug’s injury is traumatic. As we read further down the note, we see this information:\r\n\r\n<em>MRI shows partial tear of right rotator cuff. Doug is a house painter and frequently shovels out neighbor’s driveway in winter. Repetitive motion likely contributed to tear. </em>\r\n\r\nICD-10-CM includes codes for traumatic (S46.01-) and nontraumatic (M75.1-) rotator cuff tears. Dr. Frosty did not specifically indicate which kind Doug suffered, but his documentation seems to lean toward nontraumatic. After all, he is referencing repetitive motion.\r\n\r\nWe know as coders that we can’t assume and in the case of rotator cuff injuries, ICD-10-CM helps us out a little. The description for codes in the M75.1- subcategory include the words “rotator cuff tear or rupture not specified as traumatic.”\r\n\r\nDr. Frosty didn’t specify a traumatic rupture, so we’re going to use the M75.1- codes. The codes are further subdivided by the degree of the tear:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Unspecified</li>\r\n	<li>Incomplete</li>\r\n	<li>Complete</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nWe know Doug suffered an incomplete tear, so we’ll go with M75.111 for a right rotator cuff repair. We don’t need a seventh character to specify the encounter because we are using a code from Chapter 13 (diseases of the musculoskeletal system and connective tissue).\r\n\r\nIf Dr. Frosty documented a traumatic rupture, we would have used a S46.01- code from Chapter 19 (injury, poisoning and certain other consequences of external causes), and we would have needed a seventh character to indicate the encounter.\r\n\r\nDr. Frosty also sees Jocelyn, who comes in complaining of pain on the outside of her left elbow. She is having trouble bending the elbow and she experiences pain when she tries to bend it. She is also unable to turn her forearm to rotate her palm.\r\n\r\nJocelyn was making a last-minute grocery run yesterday to prepare for today’s storm. She slipped and used her left arm to break her fall. She said her arm hurt a little yesterday, but not enough to seek treatment. However, her arm really bothered her today, so she came into the clinic.\r\n\r\nDr. Frosty orders an x-ray that reveals a fracture of the left radial head.\r\n\r\nIf you look up fracture, radial head, in the ICD-10-CM Alphabetic Index, you see a note to see Fracture, radius, upper end, head. Really? They couldn’t just give me the code?\r\n\r\nWell, no, and for good reason it turns out. Once we get to Fracture, radius, upper end, head, we find multiple options:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Head</li>\r\n	<li>Neck</li>\r\n	<li>Specified NEC</li>\r\n	<li>Physeal</li>\r\n	<li>Torus</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nWe know we’re dealing with the head of the radius, which leads us to S52.12-.\r\n\r\nThe next thing we need to know is whether the fracture is displaced. Dr. Frosty doesn’t specify, but we do have a default in ICD-10-CM.\r\n\r\nA note above every section of fracture codes instructs us to code a fracture not indicated as displaced or nondisplaced as displaced.\r\n\r\nIs the fracture open or closed? Again Dr. Frosty didn’t specify, but he also did not note any open wounds. Query or guess? We know not to guess, but we don’t have to query either. ICD-10-CM includes another helpful default. This one tells us to code a fracture not indicated as open or closed as closed.\r\n\r\nNow we have an initial encounter for a closed, displaced fracture of the left radial head, which gives us code S52.122A.\r\n\r\nI certainly hope the maintenance staff clears the parking lot of snow and ice before it’s time for us to go home!',
