		'body' : '<a href=\"http://blogs.hcpro.com/icd-10/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/Penguin-with-shovel.jpg\"><img class=\"alignright size-medium wp-image-4288\" src=\"http://blogs.hcpro.com/icd-10/wp-content/uploads/2015/01/Penguin-with-shovel-300x264.jpg\" alt=\"Penguin with shovel\" width=\"300\" height=\"264\" /></a>We’re into dig out mode here in Anytown and apparently, not everyone got the memo about proper snow shoveling techniques.\r\n\r\nRichard came into the Fix ‘Em Up Clinic complaining of intense pain in his buttocks, right thigh, and right calf. He told Dr. Frosty that he spent six hours shoveling snow yesterday and today can barely stand the pain.\r\n\r\nDr. Frosty sends Richard for an MRI, which reveals a herniated disc. What information do we need to code Richard’s condition?\r\n\r\nIf you look up herniated disc in the ICD-10-CM Alphabetic Index, you won’t find it. You will find an entry for nucleus pulposus (the fancy medical name for an intervertebral disc). That entry directs you to see Displacement, intervertebral disc.\r\n\r\nWhen we get there, we find that we need some additional information, specifically where in <!--more-->the back the herniated disc is located. ICD-10-CM separates the back into:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Cervical</li>\r\n	<li>Lumbar</li>\r\n	<li>Lumbrosacral</li>\r\n	<li>Sacrococcygeal</li>\r\n	<li>Thoracic</li>\r\n	<li>Thoracolumbar</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nIf you aren’t familiar with the anatomy of the spine, now is a good time to brush up. Fortunately, though, ICD-10-CM combines thoracic, thoracolumbar, and lumbosacral intervertebral discs into one series of codes. However, each region is separated in the subseries so Dr. Frosty needs to be very specific about which disc is herniated.\r\n\r\nDr. Frosty documents the herniation is in the lumbar region, so we’re in the M51. - subsection of codes. What else do we need to know?\r\n\r\nDoes Richard have myelopathy (spinal cord compression), radiculopathy (radiating pain), or disc displacement? Richard mentioned pain in his back, buttocks, leg, and calf, so Dr. Frosty documents radiculopathy.\r\n\r\nThat gives us M51.16 (intervertebral disc disorders with radiculopathy, lumbar region). If Richard suffered from multiple herniated discs at different levels, say the lumbar and the lumbrosacral, you would need to report two codes (or one for each region if Richard had a really bad back).\r\n\r\nIn fact, category M51 features two Excludes2 notes. An Excludes2 note tells you the listed codes are not part of the code you are looking at, but the patient can suffer from both conditions. If so, you report both codes. The Excludes2 note under M51 lets you know you can report M51- codes with codes from these two series:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Cervical and cervicothoracic disc disorders (M50.-)</li>\r\n	<li>Sacral and sacrococcygeal disorders (M53.3)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nICD-10-CM does not (yet) break the codes down to the individual disc so all you need is the region(s).\r\n\r\nBernie suffered a slightly different shoveling injury. He claims he was attacked by his snow shovel. Um, Bernie, what were you hydrating with before you went out and shoveled?\r\n\r\nIt turns out, Bernie’s shovel did attack him after a fashion. Bernie was shoveling the sidewalk when his kids came out to play. He decided to stick the shovel in a snow bank and help the kids build the world’s most awesome snow fort. During construction, Bernie lost track of the shovel and it got buried in the fort. Oops.\r\n\r\nAfter completing construction, Bernie was disembarking from the fort and stepped on the shovel handle. If you’ve ever seen a cartoon character step on a rake, you know what happened to Bernie. The shovel blade came up and smacked him in the face. The kids thought it was pretty funny, especially when Bernie fell down (and went “boom!” according to his son).\r\n\r\nFortunately, Bernie’s shovel does not have a metal blade on the end (that would have been really bad). He ended up with a big bruise on his forehead and the aforementioned blurry vision. Bernie’s wife decided to bring him in to the Fix ‘Em Up Clinic as a precaution.\r\n\r\nGood thing, too, as Dr. Frosty diagnosed a mild concussion. Bernie says he doesn’t think he lost consciousness, but he’s not sure. In ICD-10-CM, concussion codes are broken down by the length of time the patient lost consciousness.\r\n\r\nDr. Frosty’s final diagnosis is a mild concussion with no loss of consciousness and a forehead contusion. That gives us codes:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>S06.0X0A, concussion without loss of consciousness, initial encounter</li>\r\n	<li>S00.83XA, contusion of other part of head, initial encounter</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nThe forehead doesn’t rate its own code apparently, so it is lumped in with other parts of the head. This is a not elsewhere classified code, meaning we have the information, we just don’t have a specific enough code. It’s not the same as a not otherwise specified code, which means the physician didn’t document the information. Maybe the forehead will get its due when we get the first round of ICD-10-CM updates.\r\n\r\nUntil then, be safe while shoveling and remember where you put your snow removal equipment.',
