		'summary' : '',
		'body' : '<a href=\"http://blogs.hcpro.com/icd-10/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/groundhog.jpg\"><img class=\"alignright size-medium wp-image-4295\" src=\"http://blogs.hcpro.com/icd-10/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/groundhog-300x157.jpg\" alt=\"groundhog\" width=\"300\" height=\"157\" /></a>And a chilly one it is. It’s also the day after the Super Bowl, which means patients with a variety of injuries arrived at the Fix ‘Em Up Clinic today.\r\n\r\nFirst is Phil, who is convinced he is a groundhog. He’s not. He’s really just a guy in a groundhog suit, but he’s sure he is indeed THE Punxsutawney Phil, seer of seers, sage of sages, prognosticator of prognosticators, and weather prophet extraordinaire. Okay, then. Dr. Jung will see you now.\r\n\r\nIt turns out that Phil (the person) had a few too many adult beverages while waiting for Phil (the actual groundhog) to make his prediction. It’s six more weeks of winter, in case you missed it. (Stupid rodent.)\r\n\r\nDr. Jung diagnoses Phil (the person) with alcohol poisoning. Off to the Table of Drugs and Chemicals we go. Coding for poisonings in ICD-10-CM is very similar to coding for them in <!--more-->ICD-9-CM. The Table of Drugs and Chemicals lists the various substances with six columns that indicate how the poisoning happened:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Poisoning, accidental (unintentional)</li>\r\n	<li>Poisoning, intentional self-harm</li>\r\n	<li>Poisoning, assault</li>\r\n	<li>Poisoning, undetermined</li>\r\n	<li>Adverse effect</li>\r\n	<li>Underdosing</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nThose choices are slightly different from the ones we currently have and underdosing is a new option for ICD-10-CM.\r\n\r\nIn Phil’s case, Dr. Jung diagnosed an accidental alcohol poisoning and also documented alcohol abuse. So we’ll need to code for that as well.\r\n\r\nWhen you look up alcohol in the Table of Drugs and Chemicals, you’ll notice ICD-10-CM includes quite a few types of alcohol. Four of them include a subentry for beverage. The alcohol usually used in beverages is ethyl alcohol, so for Phil, we would report T51.0X1A (toxic effect of ethanol, accidental [unintentional], initial encounter).\r\n\r\nFor Phil’s alcohol abuse, we need a little more information. ICD-10-CM includes codes for\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Uncomplicated</li>\r\n	<li>With intoxication</li>\r\n	<li>With alcohol-induced mood disorder</li>\r\n	<li>With alcohol-induced psychotic disorder</li>\r\n	<li>With other alcohol-induced disorders</li>\r\n	<li>With unspecified alcohol-induced disorder</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nWell, Phil does think he’s a groundhog, but is that simply a sign of intoxication or is it an indicator of psychosis? Fortunately, Dr. Jung documented that Phil is suffering from intoxication delirium and is not delusional, so we would report F10.121 (alcohol abuse with intoxication delirium).\r\n\r\nPhil is off to sober up and hopefully stop imagining he is a rodent, which brings us to Larry.\r\n\r\nLarry was a little displeased with Phil’s prognostication, so he planned to “fix that little so-and-so but good.” Larry’s plan was to shoot Phil with a shotgun, so he loaded his weapon, packed up his car, and headed off to Punxsutawney.\r\n\r\nLuckily for Phil, Larry forgot to pack his GPS, and since Punxsutawney isn’t a large town, Larry ended up missing it and wandering the wilds of Jefferson County. Larry stopped by the side of the snowy road to relieve himself (he drank a lot of coffee on his roadtrip) and took his shotgun with him. He didn’t want someone to steal it while he was away from the vehicle.\r\n\r\nShould have left the gun in the car, Larry. On his way back to the vehicle, Larry slipped and accidentally discharged his shotgun. The shell went off into the woods, where it went a little too close to a deer. Said deer decided to charge Larry, who miraculously managed to avoid the angry animal. Of course he did that by slipping again, this time landing on his back. He stayed still long enough for the deer to lose interest and head back into the woods.\r\n\r\nLarry’s immobility, however, was not due to a desire to avoid the deer. When he fell, his head hit a rock, which knocked him out. Fortunately, some locals found him and brought him in.\r\n\r\nDr. Thumper examines Larry, who regain consciousness shortly after arriving at the clinic and diagnoses a concussion with loss of consciousness (LOC). Based on Larry’s best recollection and information from the rescuers, Dr. Thumper estimates that Larry was unconscious for two to three hours. Dr. Thumper also documents a three-inch laceration to the back of the skull with no foreign body and mild frostbite of ears, fingers, and toes. The frostbite affects both ears, the fingers of the right hand, and the toes of both feet.\r\n\r\nBased on Dr. Thumper’s documentation, we would report:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>S06.0X3A, concussion with loss of consciousness of 1 hour to 5 hours 59 minutes, initial encounter</li>\r\n	<li>S01.01XA, laceration without foreign body of scalp, initial encounter</li>\r\n	<li>T33.011A, superficial frostbite of right ear, initial encounter</li>\r\n	<li>T33.012A, superficial frostbite of left ear, initial encounter</li>\r\n	<li>T33.531A, superficial frostbite of right finger(s), initial encounter</li>\r\n	<li>T33.831A, superficial frostbite of right toe(s), initial encounter</li>\r\n	<li>T33.832A, superficial frostbite of left toe(s), initial encounter</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nAll of these codes require a seventh character to indicate the encounter, but the laceration code also requires a placeholder X. The X in the concussion code is actually part of the code. You don’t need to add it. ICD-10-CM already did.\r\n\r\nThe other thing to note is the fingers and toes are only divided by laterality, not by specific digits. You’ll use the same code regardless of the number of fingers or toes affected, as long as they are on the same limb.\r\n\r\nLarry wisely decided to drop his vendetta against Phil (especially since our patient Phil is still wandering around in his groundhog getup).\r\n\r\nNow we come to our final patient of the day, Bill. Bill was so excited by the Super Bowl halftime show that he started jumping up and down on the couch. And then he missed the couch and landed awkwardly on the floor. His right ankle “crumpled and really hurt,” according to Bill. He also reported that his rear end is very painful.\r\n\r\nHowever, Bill didn’t want to miss the end of the game so he waited until today to seek treatment. His ankle is extremely swollen and Bill is unable to put any weight on it.\r\n\r\nDr. Setter sends Bill for some diagnostic imaging, which reveals a dislocated ankle with a displaced bimalleolar fracture and a fractured coccyx. Based on Dr. Setter’s documentation, we would code:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>S82.841A, displaced bimalleolar fracture of right lower leg, initial encounter</li>\r\n	<li>S93.04XA, dislocation of right ankle joint, initial encounter</li>\r\n	<li>S32.2XXA, fracture of coccyx, initial encounter</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nAgain, all of these codes require a seventh character, and two of them require placeholder Xs to make sure the seventh character is in the seventh position.\r\n\r\nMost fractures in ICD-10-CM include codes for displaced or non-displaced. Fracture of the coccyx is one of the exceptions. You only have one base code. Of course you can choose from six seventh character options, so you can actually report six different codes. You do need to go to the start of category S32 (fracture of lumbar spine and pelvis) to find the list of appropriate seventh characters.\r\n\r\nFortunately, our waiting room is cleared and we can call it a day. Just remember, don’t drive angry.',
