		'body' : 'Tobie comes into the Acme ED Tuesday complaining of stomach cramps, nausea (but no vomiting), light-headedness, and chest pain. What in the world could be wrong with Tobie?\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://blogs.hcpro.com/icd-10/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Doritos-800x612.jpg\"><img class=\"alignright size-medium wp-image-4327\" src=\"http://blogs.hcpro.com/icd-10/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Doritos-800x612-300x229.jpg\" alt=\"Doritos (800x612)\" width=\"300\" height=\"229\" /></a>Dr. H.M. Lock examines Tobie and first rules out a myocardial infarction. He also rules out a panic attack. Dr. Lock then considers an allergic reaction or poisoning. The question is, what substance was involved?\r\n\r\nTobie told Dr. Lock that she and her husband went on a date night to a Chinese restaurant Sunday night, then took the kids to a different Chinese restaurant last night. In between, Tobie confessed she consumed two (big) bags of chili cheese Doritos (because they were so tasty) and had leftover Chinese food for lunch.\r\n\r\nWith that information in hand, Dr. Lock diagnoses MSG poisoning.\r\n\r\nIf we look in the Table of Drugs and Chemicals in the <em>ICD-10-CM Manual</em> (it looks very similar to the one in the <em>ICD-9-CM Manual</em>), we do find an entry for monosodium glutamate. Note that you have to look for the whole term, not the abbreviation MSG.\r\n\r\nWe also need to know what type of poisoning Tobie suffered:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Accidental</li>\r\n	<li>Intentional self-harm</li>\r\n	<li>Assault</li>\r\n	<li>Undetermined</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<!--more-->ICD-10-CM does include two other choices in the Table of Drugs and Chemicals: adverse effect and underdosing. However, we don’t have options for those causes for MSG. That makes sense since MSG isn’t a therapeutic substance.\r\n\r\nWe’ll only use adverse effect when the patient takes a drug that was properly prescribed and appropriately administered. Underdosing is a new concept in ICD-10-CM. It again applies only to medication. For underdosing, the patient takes less of the medication than prescribed either intentionally (for example, it’s too expensive) or accidentally (because the patient has dementia and forgot to take the medication).\r\n\r\nWhich brings us back to poor Tobie, who was poisoned by MSG. Which type of poisoning did she suffer? Well, no one forced her to eat the Chinese food or the Doritos, so we can rule out assault. She wasn’t trying to kill herself, she was just enjoying some food. That eliminates intentional self-harm.\r\n\r\nDr. Lock didn’t document that the poisoning was accidental, so should we use accidental or undetermined? The default in ICD-10-CM is accidental. We would only use undetermined when the physician documents that he or she can’t determine the circumstances of the poisoning.\r\n\r\nFor example, the physician may not be sure if a patient was assaulted or intentionally took too much of a drug. That’s undetermined. Eating too much Chinese food and too many Doritos is accidental, which gives us code T65.891- on the table.\r\n\r\nSuper coders that we are, we know not to stop there. We still need to check the Tabular List for any additional characters and any notes. We find both.\r\n\r\nUnder T65 (toxic effects of other and unspecified substances) we see that we need a seventh character for the poisoning codes to denote the encounter. Since this is Tobie’s first visit for her MSG poisoning, we would use A (initial encounter), which makes our code T65.891A.\r\n\r\nBut wait, we’re not done yet. If you go all the way back to the beginning of the poisoning section (T36), you’ll see some other notes, including one to use additional codes to specify the manifestations of the poisoning.\r\n\r\nIn Tobie’s case, we would also code:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>R10.84, stomach cramps</li>\r\n	<li>R11.0, nausea</li>\r\n	<li>R42, light-headedness</li>\r\n	<li>R07.9, chest pain (unspecified chest pain)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nSequence the poisoning code first, then all of the manifestations.\r\n\r\nFortunately for Tobie, in most cases MSG poisoning resolves on its own, so Dr. Lock sends her on her way with an admonition to go easy on the MSG in the future.',
