		'body' : '<a href=\"http://blogs.hcpro.com/icd-10/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Cliff.jpg\"><img class=\"alignright size-medium wp-image-4362\" src=\"http://blogs.hcpro.com/icd-10/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Cliff-300x300.jpg\" alt=\"Cliff\" width=\"300\" height=\"300\" /></a>Poor Wile E. Coyote, Friday the 13<sup>th</sup> has not been kind to our favorite super genius.\r\n\r\nWile E. arrived at the Acme ED decidedly the worse for wear after his latest encounter with a certain speedy bird and another less-than-stellar Acme product.\r\n\r\nWile E. purchased roller skis in an attempt to increase his speed and allow him to nab his choice of prey. At first, things looked pretty good. Wile E. was in hot pursuit of his prospective dinner when said meal made a U-turn at the end of a cliff. Sadly, Wile E. did not see the cliff edge coming and continued to ski forward into space.\r\n\r\nHe maintained enough momentum that he initially appeared likely to land safely on the cliff across the way. However, this being Friday the 13<sup>th</sup> and Wile E. being the unluckiest coyote to ever live, gravity got the better of him. Instead of landing on the smooth top of the opposite cliff, he slammed into the side. To make matters worse, he then plummeted to the bottom of the gorge.\r\n\r\nAt the Acme ED, Dr. Frankenbean undertook a thorough examination of Wile E.’s wounds.\r\n\r\nAccording to Dr. Frankenbean’s documentation, Wile E. suffered multiple facial fractures consistent with hitting a rock wall at speed. So we have some traumatic fractures. The question is, which bones did Wile E. break?\r\n\r\nICD-10-CM does include a code for unspecified fracture of facial bones (S02.92-) and if you look up fracture, face, that’s where the Alphabetic Index sends you. But is that the best code to use?\r\n\r\n<!--more-->Not really. ICD-10-CM includes specific codes for the different bones of the face, such as:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Nasal bones (S02.2-)</li>\r\n	<li>Orbital floor (S02.3-)</li>\r\n	<li>Malar, maxillary, and zygoma bones (S02.4-)</li>\r\n	<li>Tooth (traumatic) (S02.5-)</li>\r\n	<li>Mandible (S02.6-)</li>\r\n	<li>Other specified skull and facial bones (S02.8-)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nSome of these subcategories are further divided to provide more specificity on the actual bone and type of fracture. In addition, all of them require a seventh character to denote the encounter.\r\n\r\nUnfortunately, fractures aren’t the worst of Wile E.’s problems. Dr. Frankenbean also documented a subdural hematoma. A subdural hematoma is a collection of blood outside the brain. The bleeding in a subdural hematoma is under the skull and outside the brain, not in the brain itself.\r\n\r\nWith a traumatic subdural hemorrhage, we also need to know about any loss of consciousness. ICD-10-CM includes 10 different codes for a traumatic subdural hemorrhage, more when you remember to add the seventh character.\r\n\r\nIf you look in the Tabular List under S06.5- (traumatic subdural hemorrhage), you won’t find a note about the seventh character. You have to go all the way back to the main category, S06 (intracranial injury) to find these notes:\r\n\r\nIncludes: traumatic brain injury\r\n\r\nCode also any associated:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Open wound of head (S01.-)</li>\r\n	<li>Skull fracture (S02.-)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nExcludes1:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Head injury NOS (S09.90)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nThe appropriate seventh character is to be added to each code from category S06\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>A, initial encounter</li>\r\n	<li>D, subsequent encounter</li>\r\n	<li>S, sequela</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nThese notes apply to all of the subcategories under S06.\r\n\r\nIn his notes, Dr. Frankenbean documented a traumatic subdural hematoma with a loss of consciousness of 48 minutes. We know this is Wile E.’s first visit for these injuries, so we would report S06.5X2A (traumatic subdural hemorrhage with loss of consciousness of 31 minutes to 59 minutes, initial encounter).\r\n\r\nDr. Frankenbean is taking a wait and see approach to treating Wile E.’s hematoma, so he is ordering observation for the coyote. We’ll check back on Wile E. next week to see how he’s doing. In the meantime, watch out for black cats, ladders, and umbrellas opened indoors.',
