		'title' : 'No pot of gold for you',
		'published' : '2015-03-17 16:30:50',
		'status' : 1,
		'summary' : '',
		'body' : '<a href=\"http://blogs.hcpro.com/icd-10/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Pot-of-gold.jpg\"><img class=\"alignright size-medium wp-image-4372\" src=\"http://blogs.hcpro.com/icd-10/wp-content/uploads/2015/03/Pot-of-gold-300x260.jpg\" alt=\"Pot of gold\" width=\"300\" height=\"260\" /></a>Liam spent this St. Patrick’s Day on a fruitless quest for a pot of gold.\r\n\r\nHe powered up for his quest by having a few glasses of green Guinness beer for breakfast. Turns out it’s not a good idea to try and make Guinness green. It requires an excessive amount of green dye.\r\n\r\nAs a result, Liam ended up suffering from:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>0X1A, toxic effect of ethanol, accidental (unintentional), initial encounter</li>\r\n	<li>6X1A, toxic effect of paints and dyes, not elsewhere classified, accidental (unintentional), initial encounter</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nYou’ll find those codes by looking in the Table of Chemicals and Drugs, just like you do in ICD-9-CM.\r\n\r\nHowever, Liam decided a little poisoning was not going to deter him from his pursuit of fame and fortune (mostly fortune). So he headed back out to follow the rainbow only he could see. Hmm, perhaps Liam also has a little R44.1 (visual hallucinations) going on.\r\n\r\nThe (imaginary) rainbow leads him into the deep, dark woods, where instead of finding a friendly leprechaun, he encounters some decidedly less friendly woodland creatures. Or at least that’s his story when he arrives back at the Fix ‘Em Up Clinic with numerous bite marks, abrasions, and lacerations.\r\n\r\n<!--more-->ICD-10-CM groups injuries in Chapter 19 (Injury, poisoning, and certain other consequences of external causes [S00-T88]) by site, not by type of injury like ICD-9-CM. If Liam suffered different types of injuries to, say his forearms, we would report codes from S50-S59. You’ll find lacerations, contusions, open bites, blisters, punctures, and fractures (among others) involving the forearms in this range of codes.\r\n\r\nNote that the codes specify laterality and encounter, so make sure you physician is documenting that information.\r\n\r\nDon’t forget your external cause codes (if your payer requires them). The external cause codes (formerly known as E codes) tell you:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>How the injury happened</li>\r\n	<li>Where it happened</li>\r\n	<li>What the patient was doing when it happened</li>\r\n	<li>Whether the injury was intentional</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nFor Liam’s trip into the woods, we could report:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>51XA, bitten by raccoon (we also have codes for squirrel, cow, pig, horse, rat, mouse, assorted birds, dogs, cats, and the always popular “other”)</li>\r\n	<li>82A, forest as the place of occurrence of the external cause</li>\r\n	<li>01, activity, walking, marching and hiking (sadly, we do not have a code for tracking leprechauns)</li>\r\n	<li>8, other external cause status (again, we lack a code for searching for gold or little green men)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nLiam is nothing if not determined, so he heads back to the woods, but gets sidetracked on the way by a field of clover. What better way to relax than to look for a lucky four-leaf clover, right? Unless you stumble into a patch of poison ivy and you, like Liam, happen to be extremely allergic to poison ivy.\r\n\r\nBack to the clinic he comes, suffering from L23.7 (allergic contact dermatitis due to plants, except food). ICD-10-CM helpfully includes a range of causes for allergic contact dermatitis, including:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Metals</li>\r\n	<li>Adhesives</li>\r\n	<li>Cosmetics</li>\r\n	<li>Drugs in contact with skin</li>\r\n	<li>Dyes</li>\r\n	<li>Other chemical products</li>\r\n	<li>Food in contact with skin</li>\r\n	<li>Other agents</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nDon’t know what caused the condition? We’ve got a code for that as well: L23.9 (allergic contact dermatitis, unspecified cause). You may hesitate to report an unspecified code, but in some cases, unspecified is the most appropriate code available. Liam may have no idea what he touched that caused the allergic reaction. Instead of forcing the physician to perform multiple tests to determine a cause, ICD-10-CM tells us to use the unspecified code.\r\n\r\nI don’t know about you, but I am experiencing some R53.83 (other fatigue) just looking at Liam’s chart. I think I’ll go have a bowl of Lucky Charms and some Jameson’s and call it a day.',
