		'body' : 'And the flowers bring pollen. <em>Achoo!</em>\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://blogs.hcpro.com/icd-10/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/Allergy-guy-1500x1136.jpg\"><img class=\"alignright size-medium wp-image-4433\" src=\"http://blogs.hcpro.com/icd-10/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/Allergy-guy-1500x1136-300x227.jpg\" alt=\"Allergy guy (1500x1136)\" width=\"300\" height=\"227\" /></a>Allergies are a fact of life for millions of Americans—approximately 30% of adults and 40% of children suffer from allergies, according to the <a href=\"http://acaai.org/news/facts-statistics/allergies\">American College of Allergy, Asthma and Immunology</a>. That’s a lot of sniffling and sneezing.\r\n\r\nWhat are all of these people allergic to? Just about everything:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Bee stings</li>\r\n	<li>Cat dander</li>\r\n	<li>Cockroaches</li>\r\n	<li>Dust</li>\r\n	<li>Grain</li>\r\n	<li>Grass</li>\r\n	<li>Peanuts</li>\r\n	<li>Pollen</li>\r\n	<li>Ragweed</li>\r\n	<li>Rose pollen</li>\r\n	<li>Shellfish</li>\r\n	<li>Wheat</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<!--more-->The list goes on and on.\r\n\r\nMost people are familiar with seasonal allergies. The flowers bloom and release pollen, and all of a sudden you can’t stop sneezing.\r\n\r\nWhen we code allergies in ICD-10-CM, we need to know the specific cause of the allergy. We also need to know the manifestation of the allergy. Finally, in some cases, we need to know how the patient came into contact with the allergen.\r\n\r\nJill just brought home a new puppy and her husband Jack has been sneezing ever since. Jack’s doctor diagnoses an allergic reaction to dog dander. When we look up Allergy, dander in the ICD-10-CM Alphabetic Index, we see two terms in parentheses—animal and rhinitis.\r\n\r\nIn ICD-10-CM (as in ICD-9-CM before it), words in parentheses are considered nonessential modifiers. If the physician documents them, great, gold star for the doc. If the physician doesn’t document them, no harm, no foul. You can still assign the code. For the dog dander allergy, we would report J30.81 (allergic rhinitis due to animal [cat] [dog] hair and dander).\r\n\r\nAllergic rhinitis can be seasonal, meaning it only shows up at certain times of the year, or it may be perennial, meaning all year long. ICD-10-CM includes a code specifically for people with perennial allergies (J30.89, other allergic rhinitis).\r\n\r\nWhat happens if the physician doesn’t know what is causing the patient’s allergic rhinitis? No problem, we have a code for that: J30.9 (allergic rhinitis, unspecified).\r\n\r\n<em>But that’s an unspecified code, you say. We’re not supposed to use unspecified codes in ICD-10-CM. They’re bad!</em>\r\n\r\nFortunately, not all unspecified codes are evil. In some cases, they represent the best information we have about the patient’s condition. The <em>ICD-10-CM Official Guidelines for Coding and Reporting</em> state:\r\n\r\n<em>While specific diagnosis codes should be reported when they are supported by the available medical record documentation and clinical knowledge of the patient’s health condition, there are instances when signs/symptoms or unspecified codes are the best choices for accurately reflecting the healthcare encounter. Each healthcare encounter should be coded to the level of certainty known for that encounter. </em>\r\n\r\nThe guidelines go on to state that a physician should not order an unnecessary medical test just so the coder can assign a more specific code.\r\n\r\n<em>Achoo!</em> Now where did that box of tissues go?',
		'meta_keywords' : '',
		'volume' : NULL,
		'issue' : NULL,
		'article_position' : NULL
