		'body' : '<a href=\"http://blogs.hcpro.com/icd-10/wp-content/uploads/2015/06/shutterstock_46900594.jpg\"><img class=\"alignright size-medium wp-image-4527\" src=\"http://blogs.hcpro.com/icd-10/wp-content/uploads/2015/06/shutterstock_46900594-300x261.jpg\" alt=\"shutterstock_46900594\" width=\"300\" height=\"261\" /></a>Richard came in to see Dr. Guts complaining of severe abdominal pain, nausea, vomiting, and blood in his stool. Dr. Guts sends Richard for a battery of tests and discovers Richard suffers from a Meckel\'s diverticulum.\r\n\r\nWhen we look up diverticulum, Meckel’s in the ICD-10-CM Alphabetic Index, we find two nonessential modifiers with the entry:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Displaced</li>\r\n	<li>Hypertrophic</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nNonessential modifiers are supplementary words that may be present or absent in the statement of a disease or procedure without changing code assignment. It doesn’t matter if Dr. Guts includes the words “displaced” or “hypertrophic” in the diagnosis. We’re still reporting the same code (Q43.0).\r\n\r\nThe only time we would use a different code for Meckel’s diverticulum is if Dr. Guts states the diverticulum is malignant. In that case, the ICD-10-CM Alphabetic Index instructs us to “see Table of Neoplasms, small intestine, malignant.”\r\n\r\nYou probably noticed that our diagnosis code falls within the congenital malformations, deformations and chromosomal abnormalities chapter of ICD-10-CM. A Meckel\'s diverticulum is a pouch on the wall of the lower part of the intestine that is present at birth, making it congenital. Patients may not have symptoms until years later.\r\n\r\n<!--more-->Dr. Guts decides that Richard’s Meckel\'s diverticulum, and consequently a portion of his small intestine, need to come out.\r\n\r\nDr. Guts admits Richard to the Stitch ‘Em Up Hospital and performs a partial resection of Richard’s small intestine. That’s all Dr. Guts documents. In the ICD-9-CM Volume 3 world, that’s enough information to report procedure code 45.62 (other partial resection of small intestine).\r\n\r\nThis code includes three different procedures:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Duodenectomy</li>\r\n	<li>Ileectomy</li>\r\n	<li>Jejunectomy</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nThat’s all fine and well in ICD-9-CM. Those procedure codes are pretty generic. We don’t need to know which part of the small intestine Dr. Guts removed or even how much.\r\n\r\nWe could be in trouble in ICD-10-PCS, though. ICD-10-PCS requires significantly more information and it does not include unspecified or nonspecific codes.\r\n\r\nOur first two characters will be pretty easy. We’re going to be in the Medical and Surgical section (first character 0) and Dr. Guts is working on the gastrointestinal system (second character D).\r\n\r\nNow things get tricky. We need to determine the root operation. We have two choices:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Excision (third character B)</li>\r\n	<li>Resection (third character T)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nBoth involve cutting a body part out or off without replacement. The only difference is how much Dr. Guts removes. If Dr. Guts removes all of a body part, we use Resection. If she only removes part of the body part, we code Excision.\r\n\r\nYou may be thinking, so what? That’s easy. Dr. Guts isn’t going to take out the whole small intestine, so we’re coding an Excision.\r\n\r\nNot so fast. ICD-10-PCS assigns body part characters to more than just whole organs or joints. Sections of organs also get their own body part values. For example, ICD-10-PCS assigns three body part characters to the liver: one for the whole liver, one for the right lobe, and one for the left lobe.\r\n\r\nSimilarly, ICD-10-PCS assigns separate body part values to parts of the small intestine:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Small intestine (fourth character 8)</li>\r\n	<li>Duodenum (9)</li>\r\n	<li>Jejunum (A)</li>\r\n	<li>Ileum (B)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nNow we need more information from Dr. Guts. What part of the small intestine did she remove and did she take out all of that section?\r\n\r\nThose questions may not be easy to answer. Unfortunately, the real human body doesn’t come with nicely divided sections like the ones you see in anatomy textbooks and drawings. Dr. Guts may not know if she removed the entire ileum.\r\n\r\nHopefully, she can tell us where Richard’s Meckel\'s diverticulum is located and she can give us the intent of the procedure.\r\n\r\nIf her intention is to remove the entire jejunum, I would code Resection. If she plans only to remove part of the jejunum, I would code Excision. The <a href=\"http://www.cms.gov/Medicare/Coding/ICD10/2016-ICD-10-PCS-and-GEMs.html\"><em>ICD-10-PCS Official Guidelines for Coding and Reporting</em></a> A11 tells us:\r\n\r\n<em>It is the coder’s responsibility to determine what the documentation in the medical record equates to in the PCS definitions.</em> <em>The physician is not expected to use the terms used in PCS code descriptions, nor is the coder required to query the physician when the correlation between the documentation and the defined PCS terms is clear.</em>\r\n\r\nThe guidelines go on to add this helpful example:\r\n\r\n<em>When the physician documents “partial resection” the coder can independently correlate “partial resection” to the root operation Excision without querying the physician for clarification.</em>\r\n\r\nOkay, so we can code a partial resection of the small intestine. As long as we know the approach, that is.\r\n\r\nHow is Dr. Guts getting to the Meckel\'s diverticulum? ICD-10-PCS table 0DB gives us five choices for an approach:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Open (fifth character 0)</li>\r\n	<li>Percutaneous (3)</li>\r\n	<li>Percutaneous endoscopic (4)</li>\r\n	<li>Via natural or artificial opening (7)</li>\r\n	<li>Via natural or artificial opening endoscopic (8)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nIf you don’t know your approaches, I strongly recommend reviewing the definitions in ICD-10-PCS. Otherwise you may be spending a lot of time searching for words the surgeon didn’t document. As with the root operations, the surgeon doesn’t need to say “percutaneous endoscopic approach.”\r\n\r\nDr. Guts documented performing a laparoscopic excision of the Meckel\'s diverticulum. She also documented visualizing the field though an endoscope. That give use percutaneous endoscopic for our approach.\r\n\r\nIf we don’t know which part of the small intestine Dr. Guts removed, we would report ICD-10-PCS code 0DB84ZZ (Excision of small intestine, percutaneous endoscopic approach).\r\n\r\nThis brings up another question. Should we query Dr. Guts for more specificity on this case? Will it help us to know, for instance, that she really performed 0DTB4ZZ (Resection of ileum, percutaneous endoscopic approach)?\r\n\r\nSure, it’s great for reporting purposes and data gathering, but is it worth sending a query for this information?\r\n\r\nICD-10-PCS procedure code 0DB84Z maps to the following MS-DRGs:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>MS-DRG 329, major small and large bowel procedures with MCC</li>\r\n	<li>MS-DRG 330, major small and large bowel procedures with CC</li>\r\n	<li>MS-DRG 331, major small and large bowel procedures without CC/MCC</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nICD-10-PCS procedure code 0DTB4ZZ maps to those same three MS-DRGs. While we want to be as accurate as possible with our coding, we probably wouldn’t send a query in this case. The additional information isn’t going to change our reimbursement. Just as in ICD-9-CM, we’ll need to pick our battles in both ICD-10-CM and ICD-10-PCS.\r\n\r\nWith only 96 days left until ICD-10 implementation, you need to make sure you have that battle plan drawn up.',
