		'title' : 'Here there be monstrous tumors',
		'published' : '2015-06-29 12:11:47',
		'status' : 1,
		'summary' : '',
		'body' : '<a href=\"http://blogs.hcpro.com/icd-10/wp-content/uploads/2015/06/shutterstock_51169732.jpg\"><img class=\"alignright size-medium wp-image-4534\" src=\"http://blogs.hcpro.com/icd-10/wp-content/uploads/2015/06/shutterstock_51169732-300x200.jpg\" alt=\"shutterstock_51169732\" width=\"300\" height=\"200\" /></a>Jurassic World is ruling the box office, so I thought I would use another blast from the past for the blog. Archeologists in Peru <a href=\"http://www.forbes.com/sites/kristinakillgrove/2015/06/23/evil-twin-ovarian-tumor-found-in-skeleton-from-16th-century-peru/\">recently uncovered the skeleton of a teenage girl</a> in a historic cemetery of the Chapel of the Divino Niño Serranito de Eten.\r\n\r\nBig deal, right? A skeleton in a cemetery. Well, this particular skeleton included something extra—83 strange bits of bone and 37 oddly shaped teeth in her abdominal cavity.\r\n\r\nThat’s not something you see every day. Archeologists believe the extra bones and teeth represent the remains of an ovarian teratoma, a usually benign tumor in the ovary that contains various tissues including hair, teeth, and bone.\r\n\r\nWhile this teratoma is really old, physicians still see these growths today. In fact, mature cystic teratomas <a href=\"http://emedicine.medscape.com/article/281850-overview#a6\">account for 10-20% of all ovarian neoplasms</a>. As a reminder, a neoplasm can be benign or malignant. By definition a neoplasm is new, abnormal growth of tissue.\r\n\r\nIf this girl came in to the Fix ‘Em Up Clinic, how would we code her condition?\r\n\r\n<!--more-->The first thing we need to know is whether the neoplasm is really benign or malignant.\r\n\r\nFor a benign ovarian teratoma, ICD-10-CM supplies three possible codes:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>0, benign neoplasm of right ovary</li>\r\n	<li>1, benign neoplasm of left ovary</li>\r\n	<li>9, benign neoplasm of unspecified ovary</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nICD-10-CM also includes a note to use an additional code to identify any functional activity.\r\n\r\nWe also see a long list of conditions under an Excludes2 note. In ICD-10-CM, we have two types of Excludes notes to take the guesswork out of what the note means. This Excludes2 note tells you that the listed conditions are not part of D27.-, but a patient can have both conditions at the same time.\r\n\r\nIf the physician documents a teratoma of the right ovary and an ovarian retention cyst, we would report two codes.\r\n\r\nHowever, if the physician determined that the teratoma was malignant, we would report a code from the Table of Neoplasms (C56.-).\r\n\r\nThe archeologists also considered other possible explanations for this odd extra tissue.\r\n\r\nThey ruled out an ectopic pregnancy (O00.-) because of the number of teeth. Note that the codes for an ectopic pregnancy begin with a capital O, followed by two zeros, just in case ICD-10-CM wasn’t confusing enough.\r\n\r\nThe archeologists eliminated lithopedion (a dead fetal mass calcified in the abdomen) as well as <em>fetus in fetu</em> (a tumor that divides into identifiable, but parasitic elements). Unfortunately, the ICD-10-CM Alphabetic Index does not include either term. So we would report a not-elsewhere-specified code. We might need to talk to a clinical person, though, to find out which code is the closest. (Hint, hint, make friends with the clinical folks now.)',
		'meta_keywords' : '',
