		'body' : '<a href=\"http://blogs.hcpro.com/icd-10/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/Firewords.jpg\"><img class=\"alignright  wp-image-3514\" src=\"http://blogs.hcpro.com/icd-10/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/Firewords-300x263.jpg\" alt=\"Firewords\" width=\"269\" height=\"236\" /></a>The Fourth of July is in the books for another year and once again, we saw an interesting assortment of patients in the Fix ‘Em Up Clinic over the weekend. Let’s take a look at some of the more challenging cases.\r\n\r\nAnytown held a Highland Horribles parade Friday night, complete with the worst-crafted floats (and worst-costumed participants) ever seen. That’s why it’s a “horrible” parade. One of the floats (complete with a fabulously fake Liberty Bell) unfortunately broke down halfway through the parade and several spectators came out to help push it out of the way.\r\n\r\nThe float collapsed as it was pushed off Main Street, and the bell, now at liberty from the float, went careening into the crowd. Most people were quick enough to get out of the way, but Bob was so busy critiquing the float removal crew that he didn’t see the giant fake bell coming at him.\r\n\r\nThe bell thankfully was not made of copper and tin, but rather of <em>papier</em>-<em>mâché</em> and chicken wire. Still, it was big enough to knock Bob down and he put out his hand to break his fall. He broke more than that. He also broke his arm.\r\n\r\nNot wanting to miss any of the festivities, Bob waited until today to come in the clinic. Dr. Setter sent Bob for x-rays and discovered a Colles’ fracture of the right arm. Hmm, I wonder if we can code that term? Maybe we’ll need to query Dr. Setter.<!--more-->\r\n\r\nFirst though, we check the ICD-10-CM Alphabetic Index and find that indeed, Colles’ fracture is a codeable term.\r\n\r\nWe know Bob broke his right arm, so we would report S52.531A (Colles\' fracture of right radius, initial encounter).\r\n\r\nAnytown held its annual fireworks extravaganza on the town common Saturday night, drawing a considerable crowd. Many residents and visitors showed up early to secure a good seat. While that plan sounded good, not everyone planned ahead for the heat.\r\n\r\nSylvia began complaining of a throbbing headache, dizziness, and light-headedness. Her friend Flo noticed Sylvia’s skin was hot and dry and convinced Sylvia to come into the clinic. Good thing, because Dr. Sunni Daze diagnosed heatstroke.\r\n\r\nHeatstroke itself is pretty easy to code. We have one code choice—T67.0- (heatstroke and sunstroke)—and three possible seventh characters.\r\n\r\nSince we know this is Sylvia’s first time seeking treatment and Dr. Daze is providing active treatment, our seventh character will be A, giving us a final code of T76.0XXA. Make sure you add the Xs or your code will be invalid.\r\n\r\nThe ICD-10-CM Tabular List also gives us some additional guidance for coding heatstroke.\r\n\r\nUnder category T67 (effects of heat and light), ICD-10-CM notes both Excludes1 and Excludes2 notes.\r\n\r\nExcludes1 means the conditions are mutually exclusive, so we can’t report heatstroke with:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Erythema [dermatitis] ab igne (L59.0)</li>\r\n	<li>Malignant hyperpyrexia due to anesthesia (T88.3)</li>\r\n	<li>Radiation-related disorders of the skin and subcutaneous tissue (L55-L59)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nHowever, the Excludes2 note means the conditions can be reported together, but are not represented by one code. So we can report heatstroke with additional codes for:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Burns (T20-T31)</li>\r\n	<li>Sunburn (L55.-)</li>\r\n	<li>Sweat disorder due to heat (L74-L75)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nThose Excludes notes apply to all of the codes in the T76 category, so make sure you check the beginning of a category for notes, and not just the beginning of the subcategory.\r\n\r\nWe also have a note to use an additional code(s) to identify any associated complications of heatstroke, such as:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Coma and stupor (R40.-)</li>\r\n	<li>Systemic inflammatory response syndrome (R65.1-)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nThat note is specific to T76.0-.\r\n\r\nNot all of our injuries happened during the day. Twelve-year-olds Nick and John became very restless waiting for the fireworks to start, so as dusk approached they took two very long sparklers, lit them, and engaged in a lightsaber battle. Needless to say, this didn’t end well.\r\n\r\nNick suffered multiple burns on his hands from the sparks shed by the sparkler. John avoided injuries, but is now grounded until he’s 18.\r\n\r\nTo code burns in ICD-10-CM, we need to know the site and severity. Dr. Daze documented multiple first-degree burns to Nick’s right and left hands and wrists, including multiple fingers on each hand. We do need to know if any of the burns were to Nick’s thumbs or just his fingers. Dr. Daze’s documentation does not mention thumbs, so fingers it is.\r\n\r\nWe’re going to report four codes for the burns—each hand gets its own code and each group of fingers has its own code. So we would report:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>T23.191A, burn of first degree of multiple sites of right wrist and hand, initial encounter</li>\r\n	<li>T23.192A, burn of first degree of multiple sites of left wrist and hand</li>\r\n	<li>T23.131A, burn of first degree of multiple right fingers (nail), not including thumb</li>\r\n	<li>T23.132, burn of first degree of multiple left fingers (nail), not including thumb</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nAs supplemental information, we can also report T31.0 (burns involving less than 10% of body surface).\r\n\r\nWe also have a note to use additional external cause code(s) to identify the source, place, and intent of the burn (X00-X19, X75-X77, X96-X98, Y92).\r\n\r\nBecause sparklers are essentially burning metal, we would report X18.XXXA (contact with other hot metals, initial encounter).\r\n\r\nWe can skip X75-X77 because Nick was not trying to hurt himself. I would not report a code from Z96-X98 either because this wasn’t really an assault. It was a pair of 12-year-olds who didn’t know any better.\r\n\r\nFor our place of occurrence, we would report Y92.830 (public park as the place of occurrence of the external cause). No seventh character needed for this code.\r\n\r\nWith that, we’re done coding our Fourth of July injuries and I for one look forward to a week with fewer explosions.',
