		'body' : '<a href=\"http://blogs.hcpro.com/icd-10/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/Angry-bull.jpg\"><img class=\"alignright size-medium wp-image-4555\" src=\"http://blogs.hcpro.com/icd-10/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/Angry-bull-300x294.jpg\" alt=\"Angry bull\" width=\"300\" height=\"294\" /></a>People do some strange things on vacation. I mean, really, really strange things.\r\n\r\nTake Mike, for example. Mike just returned from his European vacation and has come into the Fix ‘Em Up Clinic for a follow-up visit for injuries suffered during his trip. Did I mention he was in Pamplona, Spain? You know, where they let the bulls chase people through the streets.\r\n\r\nMike thought it would be fun to try and outrun a 2,000-pound enraged bovine through twisty streets in a town he’d never visited before.\r\n\r\nThis wasn’t Mike’s best plan. In fact, one of the bulls not only caught the fleeing vacationer, he gored Mike in the armpit. The Spanish doctors patched Mike up and sent him back to America.\r\n\r\nDr. Horn is seeing Mike for follow-up treatment of the wound. But what kind of wound is it? Dr. Horn’s notes say Mike was gored by a bull. The ICD-10-CM Alphabetic Index doesn’t include gore or gored as terms.\r\n\r\nFortunately, Dr. Horn also documents that Mike has a deep puncture wound as a result of being gored.\r\n\r\nWhen we look up “puncture” in the ICD-10-CM Alphabetic Index, we find a wonderfully long list of puncture sites. However, the list does not include “armpit.” Okay, thinking back to anatomy class, what is a more clinical term for armpit? Oh, I’ve got it—axilla!\r\n\r\n<!--more-->The index does include axilla, but it tells us to “see Puncture, arm.” Thanks a lot.\r\n\r\nThe listing for arm under puncture includes the nonessential modifier upper, so we’re in the right place (S41.13-).\r\n\r\nRemember that nonessential modifiers—terms in parentheses—are additional descriptive words that may or may not be present. If the physician just documented arm puncture, we would still use the same code. If the physician documented a lower arm puncture, we would report a different code (S51.84-).\r\n\r\nOur S41.13- code needs two additional characters. The sixth character denotes laterality. Right arm or left arm? We do have a code for unspecified arm, but in this case, we don’t need it. Dr. Horn documented right arm, giving us S41.132-.\r\n\r\nThe seventh character is our episode of care and this could get a little tricky. Category S41 (open wound of should and upper arm) includes three seventh character choices:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>A, initial encounter</li>\r\n	<li>D, subsequent encounter</li>\r\n	<li>S, sequela</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nSince Dr. Horn did not document any late effects of the goring, we can eliminate S. But is this an initial or a subsequent visit?\r\n\r\nDon’t be fooled by the term “initial” for A. Think of seventh character A as active treatment. It doesn’t matter if Mike is seeing a new physician. What matters is the kind of treatment Mike receives. That’s a little bit of a change from past years, so you really need to keep on top of the guidelines.\r\n\r\nHow can we tell if Mike is receiving active treatment or follow-up care? Dr. Horn called the visit a follow up. Is that enough to assign seventh character D?\r\n\r\nNo. The title of an operative report or a visit note may not accurately reflect what the physician did. Dr. Horn may be calling this a follow up since Mike was previously seen for the injury, but Dr. Horn may still be providing active treatment.\r\n\r\nLook at what Dr. Horn actually did. You may need to ask if Dr. Horn considers the treatment to be active or just routine follow up. Be prepared for the physician to be a little unsure as well. Unfortunately, there’s not bright line separating active treatment from routine follow-up care. The physician may not know.\r\n\r\n<em>The ICD-10-CM Official Guidelines for Coding and Reporting</em> offer some examples of active and subsequent care, but it’s by no means a comprehensive list.\r\n\r\nOne other piece of information may be missing from subsequent visits (or active treatment after the first visit). Did a foreign body remain in the wound? Unless Dr. Horn asks Mike and documents the answer, you have to go with no foreign body. That detail could make some of our data less precise, but we can’t code from past records. If it’s not documented, you can’t code it.\r\n\r\nDr. Horn sends Mike on his way with an admonition to avoid large angry animals in the future and recommends a more relaxing vacation next time. Anyone want to go to the beach?',
