		'title' : 'Let that ulcer bleed',
		'published' : '2015-07-31 16:56:07',
		'status' : 1,
		'summary' : '',
		'body' : '<a href=\"http://blogs.hcpro.com/icd-10/wp-content/uploads/2012/09/blood-drop.jpg\"><img class=\"alignright  wp-image-3008\" src=\"http://blogs.hcpro.com/icd-10/wp-content/uploads/2012/09/blood-drop-224x300.jpg\" alt=\"blood drop\" width=\"173\" height=\"232\" /></a>Alex comes in to see Dr. Guts complaining of fatigue and tiredness, as well as some slight abdominal pain. After performing a complete exam and blood tests, Dr. Guts diagnoses Alex with a bleeding peptic ulcer.\r\n\r\nDr. Guts determines that Alex needs surgery to control the bleeding.\r\n\r\nDr. Guts has plenty of techniques to choose from to stop the bleeding. She can cauterize the ulcer or inject medication. In Alex’s case, she decided to clip the ulcer to stop the blood flow.\r\n\r\nGenerally, this surgery is performed in the outpatient setting, but our crack coders at Stitch ‘Em Up Hospital are coding it for ICD-10-PCS so they can compare inpatient and outpatient data.\r\n\r\nSo how are they coding this procedure?\r\n\r\nWe know we’re in the Medical and Surgical section (first character 0). We know we’re in the gastrointestinal body system (second character D).\r\n\r\n<!--more-->What is our root operation? What is Dr. Guts trying to do? Well, she’s trying to control the bleeding, so maybe our root operation is Control.\r\n\r\nThe definition of Control in the <em>ICD-10-PCS Manual</em> is “stopping, or attempting to stop, postprocedural bleeding.” Clearly Control is not our root operation. Alex has an ulcer, not bleeding after another procedure.\r\n\r\nWhat about Occlusion (completely closing an orifice or the lumen of a tubular body part)? Dr. Guts is clipping the blood vessel to stop it from bleeding. However, she is not totally occluding an artery and she’s certainly not occluding part of the GI tract. So Occlusion is out.\r\n\r\nWhat’s left? The not elsewhere classified root operation Repair (restoring, to the extent possible, a body part to its normal anatomic structure and function). Repair is the root operation you use when nothing else quite fits.\r\n\r\nOkay, we now know we’re on table 0DQ.\r\n\r\nNow we need a body part. We have quite a few to choose from, including four for the esophagus (upper, middle, lower, esophagus) alone.\r\n\r\nWe need Dr. Guts to be very specific about where the bleeding ulcer is located. Fortunately, Dr. Guts is an ace documenter and we find the following information in her operative report:\r\n\r\n<em>Use EDG to reach site of bleeding ulcer at proximal end of duodenum. Placed clips to control bleeding from artery.</em>\r\n\r\nThat gives us all of the information we need to finish building our code.\r\n\r\nTable 0DQ includes a body part character for the duodenum (9).\r\n\r\nAn EGD (esophagogastroduodenoscopy) is a diagnostic procedure during which the physician inserts long, flexible, lighted tube called an endoscope through the patient\'s mouth and throat, then through the esophagus, stomach, and duodenum. The surgeon insert instruments, such as clips, through the endoscope and perform a surgical procedure. That gives us our approach: via natural or artificial opening, endoscopic (8).\r\n\r\nThe last two characters are easy because Z is our only choice for both. Our final code is 0DQ98ZZ.<a href=\"http://blogs.hcpro.com/icd-10/wp-content/uploads/2012/09/blood-drop.jpg\"><img class=\"alignright size-medium wp-image-3008\" src=\"http://blogs.hcpro.com/icd-10/wp-content/uploads/2012/09/blood-drop-224x300.jpg\" alt=\"blood drop\" width=\"224\" height=\"300\" /></a>',
		'meta_keywords' : '',
		'volume' : NULL,
