		'legacy_content_id' : 'W4597',
		'content_type' : 'article',
		'publication' : 'justcoding-website',
		'resource_type' : NULL,
		'title' : 'The armadillo strikes back',
		'published' : '2015-08-07 07:11:19',
		'status' : 1,
		'summary' : '',
		'body' : '<a href=\"http://blogs.hcpro.com/icd-10/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/Armadillo-800x761.jpg\"><img class=\"alignright size-medium wp-image-4572\" src=\"http://blogs.hcpro.com/icd-10/wp-content/uploads/2015/07/Armadillo-800x761-300x285.jpg\" alt=\"Armadillo\" width=\"300\" height=\"285\" /></a>Armadillos apparently pose more hazards to your health than <a href=\"http://blogs.hcpro.com/icd-10/2015/07/blame-it-on-the-armadillos/\">just passing on leprosy.</a>\r\n\r\nA Texas man recently <a href=\"http://www.nydailynews.com/news/national/texan-accidentally-shoots-kill-critter-article-1.2311049\">tried to shoot an armadillo three times and ended up being hit by his own bullet</a>. He claims one of the bullets bounced off the armadillo’s shell and hit him in the face. Local law enforcement believe the bullet really ricocheted off a rock.\r\n\r\nRegardless, Sam ended up with a fractured jaw. If Sam came into the Fix ‘Em Up Clinic, we would need some additional information to code his broken jaw. Specifically, which part of his jaw is broken?\r\n\r\nICD-10-CM includes nine possible locations on the jaw:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>S02.600-, fracture of unspecified part of body of mandible</li>\r\n	<li>S02.609-, fracture of mandible, unspecified</li>\r\n	<li>S02.61-, fracture of condylar process of mandible</li>\r\n	<li>S02.62-, fracture of subcondylar process of mandible</li>\r\n	<li>S02.63-, fracture of coronoid process of mandible</li>\r\n	<li>S02.64-, fracture of ramus of mandible</li>\r\n	<li>S02.65-, fracture of angle of mandible</li>\r\n	<li>S02.66-, fracture of symphysis of mandible</li>\r\n	<li>S02.67-, fracture of alveolus of mandible</li>\r\n	<li>S02.69-, fracture of mandible of other specified site</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<!--more-->No laterality necessary for these codes, but you do need a seventh character to identify the encounter. For fractures of the mandible, you have six choices:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>A, initial encounter for closed fracture</li>\r\n	<li>B, initial encounter for open fracture</li>\r\n	<li>D, subsequent encounter for fracture with routine healing</li>\r\n	<li>G, subsequent encounter for fracture with delayed healing</li>\r\n	<li>K, subsequent encounter for fracture with nonunion</li>\r\n	<li>S, sequela</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nRemember that if the physician doesn’t specify open or closed, default to closed.\r\n\r\nThe armadillo in this case waddled away scot free.',
		'meta_keywords' : '',
		'volume' : NULL,
		'issue' : NULL,
		'article_position' : NULL
