		'body' : '<a href=\"http://blogs.hcpro.com/icd-10/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/Alligator.jpg\"><img class=\"alignright size-medium wp-image-4611\" src=\"http://blogs.hcpro.com/icd-10/wp-content/uploads/2015/08/Alligator-300x198.jpg\" alt=\"Alligator\" width=\"300\" height=\"198\" /></a>Every once in a while, another facility will send us a case to review and help them code. Here at the Fix ‘Em Up Clinic, we are happy to share our knowledge as we prepare for October 1. In that spirit, we present the following case sent to us from Florida.\r\n\r\nTim and a large group of friends were out biking on a Florida highway when they came across the body of a baby alligator. The alligator suffered multiple crushing injuries as a result of being run over by a really big truck.\r\n\r\nThe alligator may have been squished, but that didn’t stop it from taking out some cyclists from the hereafter. Several of the cyclists, who were cruising at around 30 miles per hour, hit the baby gator’s body and then the pavement.\r\n\r\nTim suffered the most severe injuries, breaking five ribs, several facial bones, and his clavicle. He also suffered a collapsed lung.\r\n\r\nLet’s start at the top of Tim and work our way down.\r\n\r\n<!--more-->For Tim’s facial fractures, we need to know which bones he broke. ICD-10-CM includes codes for:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>0-, vault of skull</li>\r\n	<li>1-, base of skull</li>\r\n	<li>2-, nasal bones</li>\r\n	<li>3-, orbital floor</li>\r\n	<li>4-, malar, maxillary and zygoma bones (you’ll find codes for LeFort fractures here as well)</li>\r\n	<li>6- mandible (10 possible locations)</li>\r\n	<li>8-, other specified skull and facial bones</li>\r\n	<li>9-, unspecified skull and facial bones</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nEach code requires a seventh character for the encounter, and we’ll report one code for each location.\r\n\r\nWe checked with our Florida colleagues, who told us Tim fractured both cheekbones and his forehead. Even though Tim suffered three fractures, we’ll only report two codes:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>0XXA, fracture of vault of skull, initial encounter</li>\r\n	<li>402A, zygomatic fracture, unspecified, initial encounter</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nThe vault of the skull includes the frontal bone (your forehead). The ICD-10-CM Tabular List kindly includes that information under S02.0-.\r\n\r\nICD-10-CM codes for facial fractures do not denote laterality, so if a patient fractures both cheekbones, like Tim, we only report one code.\r\n\r\nOn to the clavicle fracture. We need to know laterality for this break as well as where on the bone the break occurred. Our choices include:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>00-, unspecified part of clavicle</li>\r\n	<li>01-, sternal end of clavicle (anterior displaced, posterior displaced, nondisplaced)</li>\r\n	<li>02-, shaft of clavicle (displaced or nondisplaced)</li>\r\n	<li>03-, lateral end of clavicle (displaced or nondisplaced)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nOur Florida friends told us Tim fractured the shaft of his right clavicle, but didn’t tell us whether the fracture is open or closed, displaced, or nondisplaced. Defaults to the rescue!\r\n\r\nICD-10-CM instructs us to use closed and displaced as defaults when the information is not available.\r\n\r\nThat gives us S42.021A (displaced fracture of shaft of right clavicle, closed, initial encounter).\r\n\r\nFor the rib fractures, we again need laterality and a seventh character for the encounter:\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>41-, multiple fractures of ribs, right side</li>\r\n	<li>42-, multiple fractures of ribs, left side</li>\r\n	<li>43-, multiple fractures of ribs, bilateral</li>\r\n	<li>49-, multiple fractures of ribs, unspecified side</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nThat brings us to Tim’s collapsed lung. If you look up lung in the ICD-10-CM Alphabetic Index, you’re directed to see condition. When you look up collapse, lung, you find the non-essential modifier (massive) and a note to see also Atelectasis.\r\n\r\nAtelectasis is a fancy (Greek) word for a complete or partial collapse of a lung or lobe of a lung. Almost everyone who has surgery under general anesthesia suffers some degree of atelectasis. Atelectasis can also result from a traumatic chest injury, such as hitting the pavement at a high rate of speed.\r\n\r\nTo code atelectasis (J98.11), the physician needs to document atelectasis. Otherwise, we’ll report J98.19 (other pulmonary collapse).\r\n\r\nNext time you’re out cycling, keep a wary eye out for flatten alligators (and deer and skunks and raccoons). Never mind, I’ll take the bus.',
